<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Confirms Result of Iraq Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Tuesday confirmed "as
absolutely true" the earlier reports on the positive result of
Russia's mediation in the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Russian presidential spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembsky told a
briefing here that the mission of Russian special envoy Viktor
Posuvalyuk in Baghdad "is continuing and is producing results"
though it is premature to go into details.
</P>
<P>
The Russian media reports said on Monday that Iraq had agreed
to let the international inspectors visit eight "presidential
sites" on conditions and expressed readiness to receive head of
the U.N. Special Commission Richard Butler in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The Russian spokesman said he found it possible to say "the
stance of Iraq is changing in the direction of the world
community".
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Iraqi Foreign Ministry's statement disavowing
the understanding reached on the inspection of several facilities,
Yastrzhembsky said, "We do not coordinate the statements of our
press service with the speeches of Iraqi officials."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Russian President Boris Yeltsin "has been
dealing with the Iraqi problem very actively by using telephone
diplomacy". On Monday, Yeltsin discussed the issue with his French
and U.S. counterparts and he may continue calling other world
leaders on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Moscow's diplomatic efforts backed by France, the Arab League
and other countries show that political and diplomatic methods are
far from being exhausted and it would be wrong to wager on the use
of force, Yastrzhembsky added.
</P>
<P>
Russian presidential envoy Viktor Posuvalyuk, also deputy
foreign minister, left for Baghdad on Monday on the second visit
to seek a political solution to the Iraq crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
