<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians not for Missile Attack Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) said in the West Bank city
of Ramallah Tuesday that the Palestinians objected to missile
attack against Israel.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with four Israeli Knesset (parliament)
members, PNA Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo stressed that
the Palestinians opposed firing missiles armed with biological or
chemical warheads at Israel.
</P>
<P>
Rabbo said that the Palestinians support the implementation
of the U.N. Security Council resolution regarding to the work
of the U.N. weapon inspectors in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Palestinian officials have declared that
they hoped the Iraqi crisis would be resolved through diplomacy
and they supported the struggle of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
PNA envoy Azzam Ahmed, who brought with him a message to
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein from PNA President Yasser Arafat,
arrived in Baghdad Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Ahmed told the voice of Palestinian
Radio that " President Arafat felt it was necessary to reiterate
the Palestinian concern for the safety of the Iraqi people and to
assure the Iraqi leadership that we would like to see a peaceful
solution.
</P>
<P>
Israeli opposition Labor party Knesset (parliament) members
Yossi Beilin, Hagai Miron, Yair Dayan and Yonel Yahal took
part in the Tuesday's meeting with Rabbo.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Ehud Barak has said that as long as the
crisis with Iraq continues, the Labor party will stand behind
the government.
</P>
<P>
He noted the government has to abide by two guide-lines:" to
keep its eyes wide open and to cooperate in a responsible manner
with the U.S.."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu also indicated Monday
that Israel has capabilities to defend itself against any
possible attack during crisis with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
After her meeting with Israeli leaders, the visiting
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has said that the
U.S. is ready to use "substantial force" against Baghdad and
nothing will shake the American commitment to Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein reportedly has set up a
special unit to maintain his biological weapons system and
keep the United Nations' inspectors from discovering it.
</P>
<P>
A senior official of the United Nations inspection team in
Iraq said last week that Iraq had a sufficient quantity of
biological weapons to destroy the population of the Israeli
coast city of Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
During 1991 Gulf War, 39 Iraqi Scud missiles were launched at
Israel after U.S.-led allied forces waged a war against Iraq.
Israel bowed to U.S. pressure not to retaliate and bomb Iraq, and
in return, the U.S. transferred Patriot missile batteries to
Israel. The patriots, however, failed to intercept the
Scuds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
