<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Unveils Ambitious Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, February 3 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian government has put
forward an ambitious budget to pursue quicker economic growth and
lower fiscal deficit in the new year.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was presented to the parliament on Monday,
envisages a 10 percent growth of gross domestic product (GDP) and
a 10 percent inflation rate while narrowing the fiscal deficit
6.4 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the Albanian government will provide 13 billion lek
(about 86.7 million U.S. dollars) in investment and encourage the
private sector to invest 13 billion lek. It plans to create 50,000
to 60,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Fatos Nano said the current government
began its work in a very difficult economic and financial
situation caused by the fake fund-raising earlier last year.
</P>
<P>
He said that with the help of the International Monetary Fund,
the country has managed to recover economic balance, bring an end
to the state of economic emergency and enter a new period of
economic reconstruction, consolidation and development.
</P>
<P>
Nano said that in the new year, the government will be strict
in implementing economic policy and curtailing public
spending. This is the only way to eventually establish a normal
financial order, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
