<HEADLINE> Iraq Criticizes UN Proposal on Oil-for-food Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said Tuesday United
Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan's recent proposal to increase
the amount of oil Iraq can sell under the oil-for-food deal was
meant to weaken its call to lift the economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the offer, an Iraqi official spokesman, who
usually keeps anonymous, told reporters that irrespective of
Annan's good intentions, it was a product of the United States,
and probably Britain.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the two countries intended to "steal" more
than 50 percent of Iraq's oil proceeds, which he said actually has
been the case, under the cover of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Annan Monday asked the U.N. Security Council to raise the
amount of oil Iraq can sell to 5 billion U.S. dollars from 2
billion dollars every six months.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed an economic sanction on Iraq, banning oil
export, in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. The U.N. and Iraq
signed the oil-for-food deal in 1996 allowing Iraq to sell the limited
amount of oil to buy food and medicine for its people.
</P>
<P>
"The only solution that could put an end to Iraqs' suffering,
is the total and comprehensive lifting of the embargo on Iraq
without any delay," said the Iraqi spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, Iraq's wealth would remain an arena for ill
intentions, under this cover or that allegation, against Iraqi
people's sovereignty, security, independence and interests, the
spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
