<HEADLINE> Report: Logs Show Lewinsky's White House Visits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Monica Lewinsky, the former
White House intern at the center of a scandal involving U.S.
President Bill Clinton, reportedly visited the White House three
dozen times after leaving her job there to work at the Pentagon in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times, citing visitation log books as the source
for its story, said Tuesday that the woman was usually cleared for
entry by Clinton's personal secretary.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Pentagon said the trips were not related to
her job at the press office there.
</P>
<P>
Officials familiar with the White House logs did not describe
Lewinsky's ultimate destination in the White House or the purpose
of her visits, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Lewinsky's White House visits have been seen by many as a
crucial piece of information as independent counsel Kenneth Starr
investigates accusations that Clinton had a sexual relationship
with Lewinsky and encouraged her to lie about it. The president
has strongly denied the allegation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
