<HEADLINE> Female Condoms to Appear in Tanzanian Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Female condoms will
appear in the Tanzanian market in the first quarter of this year,
local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The female condoms, to be distributed by the Population
Services International (PSI), are aimed at preventing HIV and
other sexually transmitted diseases (STDs), as well as unwanted
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
"We are now working on a research to determine its
acceptability in Tanzania," Dr. Richard Frank, the president of
PSI, told reporters at the Sheraton Hotel here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Frank, who arrived in Tanzania last week, said the products
will be sold at affordable prices to allow more people including
the low-income earners to have access to the gadgets.
</P>
<P>
PSI, a non-profit international organization, began the
activities in the east African country in December 1993 by
distributing Salama condoms which are widely sold across the
country.
</P>
<P>
The organization has already sold over 30 million pieces of
condoms in Tanzania. A packet of three condoms is priced at 50
shillings (640 shillings equal to one U.S. Dollar), affordable to
the majority of people.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is said to be leading in Africa with high number of
HIV/AIDS victims. As of December of 1996, there were 88,667
reported cases in the country, a number which the National AIDS
Control Program estimates to represent only 20 percent of the
real number. 
</P>
</TEXT>
