<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-03 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Expanding Press Center to Face Reporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 3 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi Culture and Information
Ministry has started to expand its press center to face the
increasing influx of foreign reporters before a possible
U.S. military strike against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Director General Uday al-Taie of the Iraqi News Agency (INA)
told reporters Tuesday that the current press center, founded
after the 1991 Gulf War, provides press services in both Arabic
(from 07:00 GMT to 21:00 GMT) and English (from 09:00 GMT to
15:00 GMT) through INA.
</P>
<P>
Al-Taie said the ministry is looking into more requests presented
by tens of foreign correspondents to obtain visas for entering
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi press center of nearly 200 square meters is now
packed with more than 100 correspondents and cameramen from
Arab and world news networks and agencies.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have threatened to launch military strikes
at Baghdad to force Iraq to comply with U.N. resolutions and to
allow U.N. arms inspectors free access to any suspected sites
including those presidential palaces in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Arrived in Cairo
Tuesday afternoon at the last stop of her week-long tour in Europe
and the Mideast to mass up support for a possible military strike
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Albright has toured France, Spain, Britain, Israel, the
Palestinian self-rule areas, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf emirates, where the U.S. maintains its forces ashore
and afloat, have backed Washington Tuesday in warning Iraq of
grave consequences if it fails to comply with U.N. demands for
granting its special commission team full access to suspected
weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors have to verify Iraq has destroyed its chemical
and biological weapons programs to pave way for lifting a
seven-year-old U.N. embargo imposed on Iraq after the 1990
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
France, Russia and China have been resisting the tough
U.S. stance and are still pressing for a non-military solution to
the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
