<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-03 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, France Call for Peaceful Solution to Iraq-UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and France Tuesday said
the current arms inspection crisis in Iraq should be solved
through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
All the concerned sides should try to end the crisis through
dialog and diplomatic efforts, Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan Ibn
Talal and France's Presidential Special Envoy Bertrand Dufourcq
said during a meeting, the Jordan News Agency PETRA reported.
</P>
<P>
They shared the view that military actions would cause
devastation to the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq arrived here Monday en route to Iraq to mediate a
settlement for the crisis. He left here for Baghdad Tuesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM)
in charge of eliminating its weapons of mass destruction from
searching presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to take military actions to
force Iraq to grant U.N. arms inspectors free access to any
suspected sites in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Hassan and Dufourcq emphasized the U.N. should respect Iraq's
sovereignty and dignity as well as international legitimacy when
making decisions related to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Dufourcq told Hassan that he would present a letter to Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein from French President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the letter Chirac would ask Saddam to cooperate
with the UNSCOM in a bid to defuse the crisis and ease the
sufferings of the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
