<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects Press Reports on Delivery of Russian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 3 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government Tuesday
rejected Turkish press reports that a strike at a factory in St
Petersburg would delay delivery of the Russian-made S-300
missiles to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, government spokesman
Manolis Christofides said he had contacted Russian Ambassador
Georgi Muratov to Cyprus over the recent report in the
Internet edition of the Turkish daily Hurriyet.
</P>
<P>
"The S-300s are not being manufactured by one factory, but
dozens of factories are co-operating together," the spokesman
said, adding the assurance is repeated that the missiles will be
delivered.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a report in the Cypriot paper Tharros that
a team of 52 National Guard officers was being trained on
the missiles system in Russia, Christofides confirmed that
"personnel for the S-300s are being trained".
</P>
<P>
He said the governments of Russia and Cyprus had decided
on a time-frame, and this would be adhered to.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus government signed a contract early 1997 with
Russian manufacturers for the purchase of the missiles, expected
to be deployed in the summer.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has responded to the arms deal with threats of a
preemptive strike if the missiles are deployed.
</P>
<P>
However, the Cypriot government has reiterated that it could
cancel the deal if President Glafcos Clerides' proposal for
demilitarization of the island is materialized, or the peace
talks on Cyprus settlement make progress.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
