<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Discusses L/Cs Guarantees With Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
and visiting Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong discussed here
Tuesday evening the efforts of several countries to guarantee
Indonesia's letters of credit (L/Cs) with a view to reviving the
country's exports.
</P>
<P>
"Our problem is that several foreign countries or banks no
longer have confidence in the L/Cs we issue," Soeharto said after
a 90-minute discussion with Goh at his residence, Jalan Cendana in
Central Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States and Australia have already agreed to
give their businessmen guarantees on various commodities Indonesia
would buy from them.
</P>
<P>
"This guarantee will smoothen Indonesia's imports," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president added that foreign businessmen or exporters need
not worry about Indonesia's capability to pay for its imports
because the country's foreign exchange reserves are enough to
finance imports for four months.
</P>
<P>
"We have foreign exchange reserves to pay for the imports
covered by our L/Cs," he declared, adding that if the L/C problem
could be solved the current monetary crisis could also overcome.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto reaffirmed his confidence that the Indonesian economy
would recover from its crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore prime minister, who arrived here at noon,
meanwhile said the basic idea that has been extended to Soeharto
is the formation of a multilateral committee with members coming
from various countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that if eight countries agree to give a guarantee of
only 1 billion U.S. dollars each for L/C from Indonesia, there
would be at least 8 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The guarantee of funds would be very important because one of
the problems faced by Indonesia is how to finance its trade,
particularly its imports, Goh stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said the economic recovery program Indonesia has embarked on
is already on the right track and Singapore would soon formulate a
paper containing details of the international guarantee plan.
</P>
<P>
Following the sharp fall of the Indonesian rupiah against the
U.S. dollar and the closing down of 16 private banks in November
last year, confidence in the country's banking sector waned. The
public withdrew their deposits and foreign banks became
increasingly reluctant to accept letters of credit issued by
Indonesian banks. The rupiah was traded at 11,300 per dollar
Tuesday, losing about 80 percent of its value since July last
year.
</P>
<P>
Goh's last visit to Indonesia was on January 13 as part of
emergency initiatives by countries and organizations including the
United States, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and Singapore
to halt Indonesia's deepening economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has pledged 5 billion U.S. dollars in standby loans
to Indonesia as part of a 43 billion dollar rescue package led by
the IMF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
