<HEADLINE> Somali Meetings Mark Peace in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Peace rallies and festivals
were held here in the Somali capital Tuesday following the
successive meetings by the main faction leaders in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people led by well known Moslem scholars, local
human rights organizations, businessmen and women groups took to
the main streets of the capital especially around the former
green lines that divided Mogadishu for the past seven years,
hailing the arrival of peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators from all the districts of the capital
including Wardhigley, Bondhere, Hawlwadag and Shingani have then
gathered at the Unknown Soldier's Monument right at the heart of
the city where the heavy fighting between Ali Mahdi and late
General Aidid erupted in late 1991.
</P>
<P>
People carried placards and national flags, while some were
waving green leaves, and they were then addressed by Somalia's
most prominent religious leader, Sheikh Mohamed Moallim Hassan,
who told the crowed to return to their Allah and the rule of his
Holy book.
</P>
<P>
Habiba Hassan Mohamud, who spoke on behalf of the women
groups, has declared their support for the Cairo Peace
Declaration and pledged that the women groups will spare no
effort in collaborating with the on-going peace activities in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The area where the Unknown Soldiers Monument lies has been
cleaned up and life has returned to it for the first time Tuesday
after it has been a no man's land since November 17, 1991.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi's press secretary, Hussein Sheikh Ahmed Kadare, who
also attended the rally has congratulated the people for the end
of all the political differences between the faction leaders.
</P>
<P>
Kadare also said that Mogadishu's airports and seaports will
soon be re-opened under joint committees.
</P>
<P>
During the rally, Maki Hagi Banadir, the famous singer, sang
his famous songs for the crowd accompanied by the Banadir Star
musical band which also played many national songs for the
jubilant people.
</P>
<P>
Another large demonstration is scheduled to take place at
Mogadishu's main soccer stadium in Wardhigley district where all
the faction leaders, influential politicians and community elders
will attend. The leaders will address the largest crowd they've
ever seen before them since the collapse of the late regime in
1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
