<HEADLINE> More Investment Urged for Mozambique's Beira </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Another international meeting
aiming at attracting investment for the Beira Corridor in
Mozambique's central port city Beira is planned for March, a
senior official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Paulo Muxanga, the Mozambican Transport Minister, said that
his government is preparing for the conference together with the
Zimbabwean government.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the joint program will promote trade
and investment, and create job opportunities for people of both
Mozambique and Zimbabwe, according to Mozambican Information
Agency.
</P>
<P>
The first Beira Corridor Investment Conference was held in
Harare, Zimbabwe in December 1996, when Mozambique, Malawi,
Zambia and Zimbabwe decided to add "development programs" into
the agreement for the corridor.
</P>
<P>
The Entrepreneurs' Council for Beira Development Corridor, set
up Monday, is composed of entrepreneurs from Mozambique's central
provinces of Sofala, Manica, Tete and Zambezia as well as those
from two Zimbabwean provinces, and it is aimed at promoting
trade, investment and job opportunities for areas along the Beira
Corridor between the two southern African countries, Paulo said.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican and Zimbabwean governments would help
entrepreneurs by channeling personnel and material resources, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Projects of Beira Development Corridor include the buildings
of highways and railway networks and the laying of petroleum
pipelines, which will link Beira port with Mutare city in eastern
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The Beira Corridor program was initiated in February last year
after a tender meeting in Zimbabwe in December, 1996, at which
Mozambique, Malawi, Zambia and Zimbabwe signed an agreement on
the establishment of the Beira Development Corridor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
