<HEADLINE> S. African Varsities in Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Days after the start of
the new school year, South African universities found themselves
in a deepening financial crisis as students fail to pay their
outstanding tuition fees.
</P>
<P>
Among student protests, many of the country's big universities
tightened debt recovery controls by adopting drastic measures
such as barring students with outstanding fees from registration
and graduation, South African Press Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The University of Durban-Westville said it was in a
"precarious situation" with total student debts of 32.6 million
Rand (6.6 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
It said about two thirds of its students had defaulted on
their fees.
</P>
<P>
The University of the North West said huge debts have put it
in a "desperate" financial position and forced it to consider all
options to cut costs, including reducing non-academic staff.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the payment of outstanding fees, the university did
not allow the 2,900 students who owed the university more than 4
million Rand (808,000 Dollars) to register or graduate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile it was consulting with student representatives on
the issue to forestall student protests, which were reported in
some universities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis flared up Sunday when 308 students at the
University of Western Cape were arrested for resisting eviction
from the student residences while refusing to pay their fees.
</P>
<P>
The university authorities said more than 52 million Rand
(10.5 million Dollars) of debt has left it unable to fulfill its
financial obligations.
</P>
<P>
The University of the Witwatersrand and the University of Cape
Town, the country's two most prestigious universities, said they
were owed about 10 million Rand (more than two million Dollars)
and 15 million Rand (3.03 million Dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, both universities expected to recoup most of the
money in the next few weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
