<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaporo Re-Elected Speaker of Kenya's New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Francis Kaporo who is loyal to
the ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU) was re-elected the
speaker of the eighth Kenyan National Assembly Tuesday with 157
votes in favor.
</P>
<P>
His rival Njelu Gatabaki of the Social Democratic Party (SDP)
got only 60 votes at the first session of the new 222-member
parliament. There were four votes spoiled and one abstention.
</P>
<P>
In a speech following his elect, Kaporo, a lawyer and former
minister in his sixties, said he will make efforts in his
five-year term starting 1998 to improve and coordinate the
parliament's operation so that it can "serve all the people of
Kenya" and "give the best to the society."
</P>
<P>
Later, Joab Omino of the National Development Party (NDP) was
elected the deputy speaker at the second ballot with 151 votes in
favor. Democratic Party (DP)'s candidate Martha Karua and
FORD-Kenya's Muknisa Kityui got 41 and 20 votes respectively.
</P>
<P>
Under the constitution, elected speakers must receive no less
than two-third of votes (around 148 votes) in parliament. Omino
got 141 votes at the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the session, some 50 opposition lawmakers
chanted and shouted slogans in demonstrations against the current
ethnic clashes which have claimed more than 100 lives in the Rift
Valley Province since January 11.
</P>
<P>
But when the elections formally started, the atmosphere was
peaceful and pleasant, eye-witnesses said, adding the whole
session went through very smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half of the 109 opposition lawmakers, led by DP
Chairman Mwai Kibaki, issued a joint statement Monday threatening
to disrupt the elections of speakers until the KANU government
effectively stops the ongoing clashes in the country.
</P>
<P>
They also called for a stay-at-home strike in capital Nairobi
Wednesday and planed to hold a rally downtown Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Peter Kimanthi said in a statement Monday
that calm has returned to violence-hit areas and no deaths have
occurred since January 26.
</P>
<P>
KANU, with 113 seats, has its slimmest-ever majority in the
new assembly elected in the country's second multi-party poll
held on December 29 and 30.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parliamentary camp consists of nine parties,
including DP with 41 seats, NDP 22, FORD-Kenya 18, SDP 16, Safina
(Ark Noah in Swahili) six and FORD-people three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
