<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece to Take Measures to Combat Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece would take new measures
this year to combat the country's growing unemployment, which
currently stands at around 10 percent, Greek Labor and Social
Security Minister Miltiades Papaioannou said today.
</P>
<P>
He said that to deal with unemployment and create 68,000 new
jobs, the Greek government would this year spend 108 billion
drachmas (about 376 million U.S. dollars). Of the amount, 81
billion drachmas (about 282 million dollars) would come from the
European Social Fund while 27 billion drachmas (about 94 million
dollars) from Greece itself, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government had worked out two principal programs to fight
the country's jobless, he said, adding that the first program
would direct at the unemployed aged between 20 and 27 and the
second one at helping the people between the ages of 28 and 64 who
had long been out of work and whose prospects of finding a job
were not good. 
</P>
</TEXT>
