<HEADLINE> Coup Plotters Expected to Be Tried Soon in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 3 (Xinhua) -- A tribunal to try Nigeria's
number two person, chief of general staff Lt.-gen. Oladipo Diya,
and 11 others being detained in connection with a coup plot is
expected to be convened this week, the military said today.
</P>
<P>
This followed last week's submission of the report of a
special investigation board at the end of its mission for nearly
one month.
</P>
<P>
At least 60 people were invited by the panel during the
investigation and some audio-video materials about the foiled
coup attempt have been shown to senior military and government
officials, traditional rulers, the diplomatic corps and media
executives.
</P>
<P>
"The tribunal would be constituted and convened by chief of
defense staff Maj.-gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar," said Col. Godwin
Ugbo, acting director of defense information.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar announced on December 21 last year the uncovering of
the coup plot, which also involves former communications minister
Maj.-gen. Tajudeen Olanrewaju and former works and housing
minister Maj.-gen. Abdulkarim Adisa.
</P>
<P>
According to the defense spokesman, all the 12 people being
held would be allowed access to "lawyers of their choice". But he
refused to say whether civilian lawyers would be accepted.
</P>
<P>
Sources here recalled that civilian lawyers were allowed
during previous trials, including those trials of nine air force
officers who were tried recently for fraud. 
</P>
</TEXT>
