<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Between COMESA Members Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Trade value between members of
the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA)
increased by 11.5 percent in 10 years from 1985 to 1995,
according to Zambia News Agency (ZANA).
</P>
<P>
In a statement released in Lusaka Tuesday, the secretariat of
the COMESA said that intra-COMESA trade increased from 834
million U.S. Dollars in 1985 to 2.5 billion in 1995.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the increase to the economic liberalization
through tariff reduction and elimination of non-tariff barriers
and restructuring and privatization among member countries in the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The secretariat stressed that the reduction of non-tariff
barriers which combined with most countries registering positive
growth rates in their economies gives hope to the attainment of a
single market.
</P>
<P>
As the year 2000 comes near, the secretariat has worked out a
program of action to push for zero tariffs rating so that the
20-member regional body can reach its target of establishing the
single market in the year, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The program includes continued assessment of revenue losses
implied by application for tariff reduction and a way of
compensation for the losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
