<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Fishing Capacity Put at 300,000 Ton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is capable of turning
about 300,000 tons of fish products annually if it harnesses only
10 percent of its fisheries potentials, an expert has said.
</P>
<P>
If the potentials were harnessed, Nigeria would meet its fish
food sufficiency, said Tunde Ajayi, acting director of the
Nigerian Institute for Oceanography and Marine Research, quoted
by the News Agency of Nigeria Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, Nigeria has 750,000 hectares of fisheries
potentials and the technological competence to harness the rich
potentials.
</P>
<P>
The Niger Delta, the largest inland river basin for example,
was currently "totally" under-utilized, he told visiting Minister
of State for Agriculture Frank Adejuwon here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"In spite of the huge potentials of aquaculture, estimated
annual fish-farm is less than 100,000 tons in all of Africa
compared with 380,000 tons in the Philippines, 519,000 tons in
Thailand, 1.6 million tons in India and 10.6 million tons in
China," Ajayi said.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the low production level in Nigeria and Africa
to what he termed the dearth of skilled aquaculture manpower.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Ministry of Agriculture to create a fisheries
extension center for the continuous training of the extension
agents and for hand-on demonstrations of innovations and
technologies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
