<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Child Labor Risks Grow in Africa: ILO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 3 (Xinhua) -- The number of child laborers
in Africa is expected to swell by at least one million annually
in the next 10 to 15 years if the continent remains predominately
rural, the International Labor Office (ILO) warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The number of African child laborers now stands at around 80
million, but could surge to more than 100 million by 2015, the
body said at a press conference here.
</P>
<P>
Child labor is an overwhelmingly rural phenomenon, with as
many of 70 percent of all child workers worldwide involved in
agricultural production, the ILO noted. Most African economies,
particularly in sub-Saharan Africa, are predominately rural.
</P>
<P>
"If present trends continue," said the ILO in a report, "at
least a further 400,000 children per year in sub-Saharan Africa
aged six to 11 would remain out of school and would, in all
likelihood, join the pool of child laborers."
</P>
<P>
Adding the increasing number of children who try to combine
work and school, there will be a total of at least one million
new child workers on to the labor market per year for the next
10-15 years, it continued.
</P>
<P>
"The poverty, population and education indicators give a
potentially bleak picture for the future of child labor in
Africa," said the report with the title of "Child Labor in Africa
-- Targeting the Intolerable."
</P>
<P>
The report is prepared for an international conference which
will be attended by employer and worker organizations and
governments of 22 African countries in the Ugandan capital city
of Kampala from Thursday to Saturday this week.
</P>
<P>
The conference, sponsored jointly by ILO and the Organization
of African Unity (OAU), aims to help develop and effectively
implement national policies to reduce and eliminate child labor.
</P>
<P>
Africa already has the highest incidence of child labor, with
almost 41 percent of all children between five and 14 years old
involved in economic activity -- versus 21 percent in Asia and 17
percent in Latin America, according to the ILO data.
</P>
<P>
Participation rates of children in the labor force are higher
in sub-Saharan Africa where nearly half of the children aged
between 10 and 14 are working.
</P>
<P>
ILO estimates suggest that in Benin, 27 percent of children
are working while in Burkina Faso 51 percent, in Mali 54 percent
and in Burundi 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures are between 40 and 46 percent in Kenya, Ethiopia,
Niger and Uganda and between 20 to 30 percent in Cote d'Ivorie,
Nigeria and Zimbabwe, said the ILO report.
</P>
<P>
In the developing world, Africa has also the highest
participation rate of girls -- approximately 37 percent of girls
work across the continent, compared with 20 percent in Asia and
11 percent in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Primary schooling, a key indicator of child labor levels,
shows that the actual number of children in the primary school
range (six to 11 years old) who are not enrolled in school jumped
by some two million from 1990 to 1995 to hit nearly 40 million.
Two-thirds are girls.
</P>
<P>
Household work is reported to be the main reason for about
one-third of the youngsters who do not attend the school,
according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
