<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's ANC Announces Team to Probe Gauteng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 3 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
party African National Congress (ANC) Tuesday announced a
three-member internal commission to probe corruption allegations
against new Gauteng Premier Mathole Motshekga.
</P>
<P>
Gauteng, where Johannesburg and Pretoria are situated, is the
richest province in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The commission would have to submit its final report with its
findings and recommendations to ANC's decision-making body, the
National Executive Committee, by March 2 this year, ANC
Secretary-General Kgalema Motlanthe said in a media statement.
</P>
<P>
Motlanthe said the commission's terms of reference were to
investigate and report on certain allegations emanating from
media reports on the alleged improper conduct of Motshekga during
the period from 1986 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission would report on:
</P>
<P>
-- allegations concerning Motshekga's possible involvement in
the alleged fraudulent administering and unapproved use of
international donor funding;
</P>
<P>
-- allegations of a lack of financial accountability and
inadequate planning as far as international donor funding is
concerned;
</P>
<P>
-- allegations concerning nepotism and autocratic management;
</P>
<P>
-- the exact nature of Motshekga's relationship with anybody
in so far as it may have had a negative effect on the ANC.
</P>
<P>
The newly sworn-in premier was alleged to have mismanaged
funds from a Dublin-based company which were to have been used
for legal clinics during the apartheid years.
</P>
<P>
He was also reported to have lied about the date he resigned
from a company involved in the province's high stakes contest for
gambling rights.
</P>
<P>
However, Motlanthe said the resignation date did not warrant
any investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
