<HEADLINE> UN Humanitarian Team Visits Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 3 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations humanitarian
team visited Sierra Leone Monday to assess the humanitarian needs
of civilians suffering from UN and regional sanctions against the
west Africa's ruling military junta.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here Tuesday said the team of four officials
crossed by road from Guinea to visit the Northern Province
capital Makeni and other towns in the region.
</P>
<P>
The report, however, quoted the special UN envoy for Sierra
Leone Francis Okello as saying that any immediate large-scale
assistance would be impossible until peace-keepers are deployed
in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Full relief operations can only start when ECOMOG (west
Africa's peace-keeping force) and UN troops are deployed," Okello
reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the UN sent a fact-finding team to Freetown to
assess what is needed to launch humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
The UN in October last year imposed sanctions against the
Sierra Leonean military junta led by Major Paul Johnny Koroma,
who came to power last May in a military coup that overthrew
elected civilian president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Media reports said the food situation in Sierra Leone is
grave, with starvation growing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
