<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Internal Reforms Should Slow Down Enlargement: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Polish Prime Minister
Jerzy Buzek today expressed the hope that the slow-moving
internal reforms of the European Union (EU) would not pose a
hindrance to the bloc's enlargement into eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl,
Buzek said that he expected very difficult membership negotiations
with the EU, which are due to be formally launched on March 31.
</P>
<P>
During the negotiation process and implementation of its
results, Poland would continue to count on Bonn's assistance, said
Buzek, who started a two-day visit to Germany today.
</P>
<P>
There have been controversies within the EU as to how to
arrange the priority between EU internal reforms and its
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
While France says that the EU should first make progress on its
reforms before taking in any new members, Germany hopes that
reforms and enlargement should go parallel.
</P>
<P>
Although the EU has not set any date for taking in new members,
none of the 11 selected candidate states, including Poland, is
expected to join the 15-nation bloc before the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
As to Poland's membership in the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), Buzek expressed the hope that all 16 NATO
members would give the green light in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders agreed last year to take in Poland, the Czech
Republic and Hungary in 1999 as the first wave of new members.
However, their memberships have still to be finally endorsed by
parliaments of all the current NATO member states.
</P>
<P>
According to German government spokesman Peter Hausmann, Kohl
had assured Buzek that Germany would continue to support Poland in
its efforts to prepare for joining both NATO and the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
