<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quebec to Fight High Suicide Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada's French-speaking
province of Quebec has said it is determined to fight the high
suicide rate, which is at 19 for every 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The rate is the third highest in the industrialized world,
behind only Hungary and Finland, whose suicide rates are at 34 and
27 for per 100,000 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Quebec Health Minister Jean Rochon has announced that his
government will spend over 700,000 dollars (480,000 US dollars)
over three years on prevention programs and public education.
</P>
<P>
The government has already spent close to 2.5 million dollars
on the suicide problem, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
Suicides have risen progressively in Quebec since the early
1970s, with especially high numbers in 1982, 1983 and the
beginning of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Painful economic recessions are "surely an additional factor
that can probably increase the risk of those people" who took
their own lives, Rochon was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed any suggestion that the constitutional debate may
have driven the suicide rate up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
