<HEADLINE> European Shares End at New Record Highs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
continued to rally today and all ended at new record closing
highs, overcoming the influence of weakness in New York and a bout
of early profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
Britain's FTSE 100 index of leading shares closed up 13.8
points at 5,612.8, a fifth consecutive record high.
</P>
<P>
Takeover activity dominated the news as several predators made
their moves. And drug stocks came in for a wave of profit-taking
after Monday's jump.
</P>
<P>
Business was also boosted by expectations that interest rates
are unlikely to move following the Bank of England's policy
meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
German shares in Frankfurt ended at a second consecutive record
high in floor trade following a shaky start and prompted by Wall
Street's overnight performance.
</P>
<P>
The DAX-30 index closed at 4,532.52, up 9.71 points on the day.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC-40 index finished the session at its fourth
straight record close, although the index was only up 0.93 points
at 3,188.43.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that share prices ended little changed as the
market entered a consolidation phase after the sharp gains of
recent sessions, and despite caution, trading remained active.
</P>
</TEXT>
