<HEADLINE> Israel Prepared for Iraqi Attack, PM Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said Tuesday that Israel has been prepared for
any possible Iraqi attack.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told a press conference that Israel has been working
on tackling Iraqi threat either independently or with other
countries.
</P>
<P>
He said though Israel is not involved in the Iraqi crisis, he
has not know of another country as prepared to protect its people
as Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We can clearly say that in Israel there is the know-how, the
planing, the thought and preparedness on one of the highest level
in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
The situations in the Middle East have become tense after the
United States threatened to take military actions to force Iraq to
grant free access to the arms inspectors of the United Nations in
charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Israel has taken precautions, including deploying the
American-made Patriot anti-missile missile, to ward off Iraqi
retaliation for possible U.S. military strikes.
</P>
<P>
During the 1991 Gulf War, in which the U.S.-led multi-nation
forces drove the Iraqi troops out of Kuwait, Iraq fired 39 Scud
missiles at Tel Aviv in retaliation, causing heavy damage of
property.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler said
that Iraq has sufficient biological weapons to destroy Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli officials have made efforts to calm the public.
Netanyahu's adviser David Bar-Illan has said the military
capability of Iraq at this point is not comparable to that in
1991, and the chance that Israel will be attacked is slim.
</P>
<P>
Israel's defense officials also have maintained that Iraq has a
few missiles armed with non-conventional warheads and that there
is only the slightest chance that Iraq would use them or try to
involve Israel in the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
