<HEADLINE> Canada's Building Activity in High Gear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada's building sector was in
high gear last year, with the issued building permits hitting a
seven-year high, Statistics Canada reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 31.5 billion Canadian dollars (21.7 billion
U.S.dollars) worth of building permits was issued across the
country last year, up 20.6 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
Yet, it is still less than the 32.2 billion Canadian dollars in
1990 and fell well short of the record 40 billion dollars in
permits set in 1989, the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the value of building permits for housing sector
increased 17.9 percent to 18.5 billion Canadian dollars, the
second consecutive annual increase of that magnitude.
</P>
<P>
The historically low mortgage rates, stable prices and record
activity in the resale market helped to push high the value of
building permits.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, construction intentions in the non-residential
sector rose 24.6 percent to 13.0 billion canadian dollars, the
agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
