<HEADLINE> Germany: Export Credits Guarantees for Asia Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Germany will continue providing
guarantees on export credits with premiums unchanged for Southeast
Asian countries affected by financial turmoil, Economics Minister
Guenter Rexrodt announced Tuesday here.
</P>
<P>
The guarantees insure German exporters against the risk that
they will not be paid by their clients.
</P>
<P>
Rexrodt showed confidence in the Asian economies, saying there
was no reason so far to downgrade these countries, which he said
remained reliable clients.
</P>
<P>
No rise in non-payment has occurred due to the Asian crisis, he
said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Rexrodt said Germany was likely to adopt a new
premium system backed by the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD) in the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Bonn's current obligation on exports to Indonesia, Thailand,
the Philippines, Malaysia and South Korea totals 25 billion marks
(13.8 billion U.S. dollars), but the actual sum outstanding was
estimated at 17 billion marks (9.4 billion dollars) with some of
the invoices having probably been paid, it is reported.
</P>
<P>
The five countries usually claim a some 10 percent share of
Bonn's guarantees on export credits.  
</P>
