<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Sees Rising Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
expects inflation to have increased by slightly below 7 percent in
January mainly due to the lingering effects of the weak Philippine
peso on prices of basic commodities.
</P>
<P>
Socioeconomic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito said Wednesday
that no other factors are seen to drive up prices as there is
enough supply of food and oil products.
</P>
<P>
The projected inflation rate is higher than the 5 percent
recorded in January 1997 and the 5.8 percent for the entire 1997.
</P>
<P>
Despite the expected high inflation for last month, Habito said
there is no cause for worry that inflation for 1998 will zoom to
double digit.
</P>
<P>
The first quarter is seen to be a difficult time for the
economy due to the present currency crisis and economic planners
are working hard to keep inflation at the projected 7.5 to 8.5
percent, Habito said.
</P>
<P>
"To keep inflation down, monetary discipline remains crucial.
Measures to address supply bottleneck are also continuously
undertaken including those directed at El Nino-affected areas," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The government sees a zero growth for the agricultural sector
for 1998 as against 2.8-percent growth last year due to the
continuing effects of the El Nino on major crops. And this is
expected to drive up prices of food.
</P>
<P>
But Habito said a price hike spiral as a result of wage
increases is being avoided by upholding the regional mechanism for
wage determination rather than a nationally mandated minimum wage
adjustment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
