<HEADLINE> India's Exports Dip Further in December Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 4 (Xinhua) -- India's export growth
continued to be sluggish in December last year with shipments from
the country declining by 5.51 percent from a year earlier in U.S.
dollar terms, an official press release said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Exports during December 1997 are valued at 2,609.69 million
U.S. dollars, which is 5.13 percent lower than the level of
2,750.85 million U.S. dollars in December 1996," the release said.
</P>
<P>
December export performance was the second worst for the
current fiscal year (April 1 1997-March 31 1998). Shipments from
the country witnessed a 10.08-percent drop in April before
registering a positive trend. The trend turned negative again in
November when exports went down by 0.95 percent.
</P>
<P>
Overall, India's exports between April and December had
increased by a meager 3.31 percent, against a 6.36-percent growth
posted during the same period of the previous year and an all-time
high of 24.47 percent in 1995-96, the release further said.
</P>
<P>
The decline in exports also sent trade deficit soaring to over
4.478 billion dollars from 3.248 billion dollars during the same
period of the previous year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
