<HEADLINE> Factory Directors Removed For Quality Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Quality control inspectors now
have a bigger say in China. Forty-nine factory directors have been
removed from their posts for making poor quality goods, under
provisions of the State Bureau of Technical Supervision.
</P>
<P>
According to sources at the bureau, the qualification rate of
local products has remained at 75-to-78 percent, though the
quality of home-made goods has been stable and generally improving.
</P>
<P>
The central government has attached great importance to quality
control and has repeatedly ordered the punishment for leaders of
factories that fail twice to pass quality check-ups. A series of
laws and regulations have been issued to this effect.
</P>
<P>
With the enforcement of these laws, the bureau has stepped up
its efforts to supervise the quality of industrial products.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the director of a local explosion-proof motor factory
in north China's Shanxi Province was deprived of his title to
become the first casualty of stricter enforcement of quality
standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
