<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Japanese Defense Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Defense Minister
Chi Haotian and Japanese Defense Agency Director-General Fumio
Kyuma agreed on Wednesday to promote bilateral defense ties
through more exchanges between defense authorities of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during their talks at the Japanese
Defense Agency in Tokyo, the first Sino-Japanese defense
ministerial talks since May 1987. Chi has been in Japan since
Tuesday for a six-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
Chi said that friendly relations and cooperation between China
and Japan, two close neighbors separated only by a strip of water,
are not only in their own fundamental interests but also conducive
to peace and stability in Asian-Pacific region and the world at
large.
</P>
<P>
Developing long-term, stable Sino-Japanese friendly ties is the
consistent policy of the Chinese government, Chi said.
</P>
<P>
Recalling bilateral ties since 1972 when the two countries
normalized their diplomatic relations, Chi noted that the overall
relationship between China and Japan has been good and the leaders
of the two countries have maintained close contacts and dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Touching on historical issues, Chi said that Japan adopting a
correct attitude toward historical issues will help maintain the
political foundation for Sino-Japanese ties and deepen the mutual
understanding and trust between Japan and its Asian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the updated guidelines for Japan-U.S. defense
cooperation, Chi said that China is concerned about the guidelines
because Taiwan is involved. If Japan can show a more definite
stance on Taiwan, it will help China clear doubts about the
guidelines, Chi added.
</P>
<P>
Chi hoped that Japan will continue to go along with the road of
peaceful development.
</P>
<P>
Kyuma told Chi that Japan will abide by the China-Japan Joint
Communique and the China-Japan Treaty of Friendship and Peace and
that Japan would advance relations with China on the basis of the
two documents.
</P>
<P>
On the new guidelines for Japan-U.S. defense cooperation, Kyuma
said that the guidelines are solely bilateral and are not directed
at any third country.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Japan's basic stance has been reflected in the
China-Japan Joint Communique, Kyuma said that Japan only maintains
unofficial ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The two men also agreed to increase military exchanges between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Chi invited Kyuma to visit China within this year, Kyuma
accepted the invitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
