<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, US Revive Transatlantic Free Trade Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
the U.S. have revived plans for building a transatlantic free
trade area, said European Report published here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A decision on whether to start formal talks on the plans is
expected by April, according to the twice-weekly newsletter.
</P>
<P>
European Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan hopes that the
possible liberalization of trade flows between the two sides can
help iron out the numerous transatlantic trade disputes between
them.
</P>
<P>
Officials from both sides have been studying ways of slashing
tariff and non-tariff barriers between them, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The plans would be based on the New Transatlantic Agenda (NTA),
signed by the two sides in Madrid in December 1995, which created a
framework for cooperation on trade, security and other issues.
</P>
<P>
In the run-up to the Madrid meeting, there were suggestions
that it could launch talks on a Transatlantic Free Trade Area, or
TAFTA, but in the end the NTA only included a commitment to
studying ways of creating a "transatlantic marketplace." 
</P>
