<HEADLINE> Manila to Implement Labor Intensive Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
implement labor-intensive projects costing 10 billion pesos (250
million U.S. dollars) to provide jobs to laid-off workers
adversely affected by the current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed Wednesday by Acting Labor Secretary
Cresenciano Trajano following a national employment conference on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of the projects is included in the
Commitment to Action for Employment which contains short- and
long-term employment strategies to prevent layoffs, Trajano said.
</P>
<P>
More than 900 representatives attended the conference Monday to
re-study the government's employment program in the midst of the
unexpected financial crisis affecting many countries in the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the job-creation projects, the government will
also develop and strengthen loan mechanisms for small and
medium-sized enterprises, especially those engaged in export
business, Trajano said.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department, in particular, will take the lead in
tapping the State Insurance Fund for setting up a 200 million peso
(5 million dollars) special loan window for displaced workers.
</P>
<P>
It will recommend to the congress that the overseas employment
sector be given tax incentives to promote overseas marketing and
job generation.
</P>
<P>
The conference asked concerned government agencies to simplify
the system for the issuance of business permits to reduce waiting
time of investors and prevent the loss of investment
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department has warned of massive layoffs of domestic
workers and repatriation of Filipino workers overseas due to
economic difficulties brought about by currency crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
