<HEADLINE> Two Fans Injuried in English Soccer Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Two fans were sent to hospital
and 29 arrested in the second English soccer match marred by
violence, police and club officials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A female steward and a ball-girl were treated after being
attacked by fans during the F.A. Cup fourth round replay between
Reading and Cardiff at Elm Park, Reading, on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Reading won on penalties following a 1-1 draw after extra-time.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, a linesman was knocked unconscious by a spectator
during a first division match between Portsmouth and Sheffield
United.
</P>
<P>
Reading stadium manager Ray Booth said a total of six Reading
fans were treated after being hit by coins thrown by Cardiff fans
and that two were taken to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Police said two Cardiff fans were charged with throwing
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Twelve people were still in custody on Wednesday and 17 had
been charged and released on bail. Most of those were charged with
being drunk and trying to enter a sports ground, a police
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
Violence in English soccer has been largely contained in recent
years after English clubs were banned from European competition
for five years in 1985 following the Heysel stadium tragedy.
</P>
