<HEADLINE> Eastern Europe's "Bag Merchants" Returning to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 4 (Xinhua) -- More and more "bag merchants"
from eastern Europe, mainly from Russia, are returning to the
South Korean market due to sharp devaluation of the country's won
against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
A report issued the Korea Trade-Investment Promotion Agency
(KOTRA) said Wednesday that the so-called "bag merchants" have
started to return to South Korea recently as the won's
depreciation has resulted in cheaper goods and bigger profits for
them.
</P>
<P>
Most bag merchants are buying up daily necessities like
processed food products, clothing and footwear in Seoul's
Tongdaemun and Namdaemum markets while some have begun to buy
products such as furniture and electronic home appliance,
including refrigerators, color TVs and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
The bag merchants are mainly from the former Soviet republics.
The number from Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan is on the rise.
</P>
<P>
KOTRA predicted that some 50,000 bag merchants will visit South
Korea this year, creating a market of 400 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bag merchants flew into South Korea in early 1990s after
the former Soviet Union disintegrated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
