<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Chief Outlines China's Defense Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Defense Minister
Chi Haotian said here Wednesday that China, with economic
development as its priority task, pursues a defensive military
policy.
</P>
<P>
"Defending the national independence, sovereignty, unity and
security, promoting the reform and opening-up and the development
of the national economy and safeguarding peace and stability in
the neighboring region and the rest of the world constitute the
core and substance of China's national defence policy," said Chi
in a lecture given at Japan's National Institute for Defense
Studies.
</P>
<P>
China, as a developing country, would not increase the defense
budget sharply as long as no serious threat to its national
sovereignty and security arises, said Chi who arrived here Tuesday
for the first official visit by a Chinese defense chief.
</P>
<P>
China aims to build a smaller but more effective army, which
will help improve the environment for global arms control and
disarmament, build trust between countries and enable China to
concentrate on economic development, he added.
</P>
<P>
Commitment to safeguarding world peace and promoting the
progress of mankind is also a key component of China's defense
policy, said Chi, who is also vice chairman of China's Central
Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
"China will not seek hegemony, invade any other countries to
expand its territory, set up military alliance with any other
countries, or station troops or build military bases abroad," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
China's defence building is not directed at any other countries
nor will it pose any threat to them, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
