<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Rejects Protest over Death Verdict on German </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi Wednesday refuted Bonn's protest to Iran's death
sentence on a German national, stressing that the death verdict
should not become a political affairs between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA reported that Kharrazi
expressed amazement at the stance adopted by the German
government and the country's media towards the trial of the
German citizen Helmut Hofer in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said that "the simple court case should not be
transformed into a political issue and Iran-Germany relations are
in need of tranquility," adding that Iran's judicial laws allow
the defendant to appeal any possible verdicts.
</P>
<P>
Hofer, 54, a German merchant, was sentenced to death on charges
of having "forbidden sexual relations" with an Iranian Muslim
woman. A final verdict has not been issued after the case was
handed over to the Iranian higher court.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old Iranian woman was arrested on September 21 last
year at Tehran international airport for wearing "non-Islamic
dress" and claimed to be married with Hofer after
interrogations. However, Hofer rejected the woman's claims.
</P>
<P>
Under the Islamic laws, sexual contact between a non-Muslim
man and a Muslim woman is considered as "a grave wrongdoing."
However, the Iranian woman escaped the death penalty because she
was unmarried and was sentenced to be whipped instead.
</P>
<P>
Despite his denial, Hofer was sentenced to death by an Iranian
court. The German government has launched a protest to the death
sentence on its citizen by summoning Iran's charge d'affaires in
Bonn, claiming that the verdict violated all principles of justice
and would be face harsh condemnation not only in Germany but also
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi Sunday
also stressed that the trial has been conducted by an official
court and in accordance with the independence of the Iranian
judiciary.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and Germany were cooled down last April
after a Berlin court accused Iranian leaders of sponsoring
assassination of four Iranian rebel Kurdish leaders in Berlin in
1992.
</P>
<P>
The Berlin court rule triggered a diplomatic row between Iran
and members of the European Union (EU), which recalled their
ambassadors from Tehran in a protest. The two sides ended their
dispute last November after the EU states agreed to return their
ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the trial of the German national would
trigger a new roun order to convince the Iranian authorities to
withdraw the death sentence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
