<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Proposes Charter on International Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive arm, Wednesday recommended in a
document to launch an international debate regarding global
communications policy.
</P>
<P>
The Commission also recommended in the document to set a
framework for international policy cooperation and to start a
process which could lead to the adoption of an international
communications charter.
</P>
<P>
An international charter would be a multi-lateral understanding
on a method of coordination to remove obstacles for the global
electronic marketplace, the EU executive body said in a statement
issued in Brussels Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The charter would recognize the work of existing international
organizations and promote the participation of private sector and
relevant social groups, but it would neither be legally binding
nor would it establish an international supervisory authority, the
Commission said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that the charter could be agreed by or in the
course of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
