<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Slams U.S. Policy Over Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
warned U.S President Bill Clinton on Wednesday that using force to
resolve the Iraqi crisis may provoke a world war.
</P>
<P>
Clinton "might run into a world war by his actions. He is
acting too loudly. Such weapons should be handled accurately." the
ITAR-TASS quoted the Russian president as saying.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Kremlin with regional governors, Yeltsin warned
Clinton against voicing threats to use planes and bombs against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The latest American moves were "quite unlike Clinton," he said,
stressing that Russia did not support the U.S. intention to
resolve the Iraqi crisis by means of force.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia "would seek its own ways" and would spare
no efforts to prevent the use of force.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Yeltsin held telephone consultations with French
President Jacques Chirac and British Prime Minister Tony Blair on
ways to solve the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov also had telephone
talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The latest crisis over Iraq began when President Saddam Hussein
refused to allow U.N. weapons inspectors to check some 60 sites,
including about 40 presidential palaces, on ground of national
sovereignty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
