<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1998 Crucial Year for Macao's Handover: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, February 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official said
here on Wednesday that Macao has entered the crucial stage in the
preparation for a smooth handover of power.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qiren, director of the Xinhua News Agency Macao Branch,
said at a grand reception for the Chinese Lunar New Year that
there are three major tasks to be done in 1998 for a smooth
handover next year.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, a breakthrough should be made in the localization of
senior civil service, as the three major transitional issues --
the localization of civil service, the localization of law and
the use of Chinese as an official language -- should be resolved
without any delay, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Preparatory Committee for the Macao Special Administrative
Region (SAR) will be established in time and will start operation
on full scale in 1998, he added.
</P>
<P>
And thirdly, more efforts are needed in promoting economic
growth and social stability so that a smooth transition will be
maintained in Macao.
</P>
<P>
"Those three are the most urgent tasks in the final stage of
transition," he stressed. "It will be a crucial year, a year which
 demands down-to-earth efforts by all sides."
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 people, including Macao Governor Vasco Rocha
Vieira, senior government officials, leaders of local communities
and other celebrities attended the annual reception.
</P>
<P>
While stressing progress in transitional affairs over the past
year, Wang expressed the hope that Macao residents would play a
more active role and make further contribution to Macao's
transition.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that all Macao residents shall be equal before
the law, and shall be free from discrimination, irrespective of
their nationality, descent, race, sex, language, religion,
political persuasion or ideological belief, educational level,
economic status or social conditions.
</P>
<P>
"Macao will continue to be a multiple society, and different
communities should live in peace with one another," he
said. "Macao will have an even better future under the policy
of 'Macao people administering Macao' and a high degree of
autonomy."
</P>
<P>
In return, Macao Governor Vasco Rocha Vieira said in his speech
 that Portugal and China are making great efforts for the
realization of a smooth handover and the implementation of the
policy of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
"The open and active dialogue between the Portuguese and
Chinese governments on Macao's current affairs and its future is
the best assurance that December 20, 1999 will not mean the end of
 a historical procedure, but the start of a road along which Macao
 will march towards development, prosperity, the establishment of
uniqueness and autonomy, and play its due strategic role within
China," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
