<HEADLINE> 19 Killed By High Methanol-Content Drinks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen people have died and
others hospitalized since Jan. 26 in Shuozhou City, north China's
Shanxi Province, after drinking alcohol containing excessive
amounts of methyl alcohol during the Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
Officials said 142 people are still under medical care in local
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
Suspects believed to be involved in making and selling the
fatal drinks have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
According to official reports, the drinks were made by a local
man who had added 361 grams of methanol to every liter of the
alcoholic drinks, which surpassed the national standards by 902
times. The poisonous alcohol was sold wholesale to a private
retailer in the city.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has expanded much effort to resolve
the case. Both Hu Fuguo, Secretary of the Provincial CPC
Committee, and Governor Sun Wensheng have visited the victims in
hospital.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Governor Du Wu'an has led a special team to deal with
the case. Meanwhile, local people have been informed of the
incident to prevent further spread of the poisonous drinks.
</P>
<P>
A 40-member medical team has been formed of experts from major
hospitals in the province to provide emergency check-ups and
treatment for the victims.  
</P>
</TEXT>
