<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossils of Earliest Multicellular Animals Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Fossils of multicellular
animals dating back 580 million years have been discovered in
southwestern China, a leading Chinese scientist announced here
today.
</P>
<P>
These are believed to be the earliest multicellular animals
living on Earth and are more than 20 million years earlier than
Ediacaran biota found in Australia which had been regarded as the
earliest such animal, said Chen Junyuan, professor with the
Nanjing Institute of Geology and Paleontology under the Chinese
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The discovery could lead to significant breakthroughs in
exploring the evolution of early life on the globe, experts say.
</P>
<P>
Professor Chen discovered the fossils in August and September
last year in Weng'an County of Guizhou Province with Li C.-W., a
professor with the National Tsinghua University of Taiwan, hence
naming them "Weng'an fossils".
</P>
<P>
The fossil fauna include large quantities of tiny multicellular
animals and their embryos, which proved to be the earliest
multicellular animals after the late pre-Cambrian period when
ground temperatures rose, land glaciers melted and sea levels rose.
</P>
<P>
Research shows that the animals existed more than 50 million
years earlier than the fossils of animals during the Cambrian
explosion found in Chengjiang County of southwest China's Yunnan
Province.
</P>
<P>
What's more important, Chen said, is that the fossils are
perfectly preserved. It is discernible that the sponges, only 0.5
to 0.75 millimeters, consist of cells of different types. "It's
amazing that the cellular pattern of such animals resembles that
of modern sponges," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, many fossils of the sponges' embryos and larvae
have been found.
</P>
<P>
Sponges were the most primitive species among multicellular
animals. Before the Weng'an discovery, scientists studying
multicellular animals before the Cambrian explosion had to rely on
controversial fossils.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
