<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Calls for New Security Concept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian on Wednesday called for the establishment of a new
security concept to seek a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a lecture to Japan's National Institute for Defense
Studies, the visiting Chinese defense minister said that the
security system based upon military alliance and military build-up
during the Cold War period approved to be unable to build peace.
</P>
<P>
Neither expanding military blocs nor strengthening military
alliance would be conducive to world security, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Security should rely on mutual trust and the links of common
interests," Chi said.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister then outlined three aspects of the new
security concept.
</P>
<P>
He said that first of all, the state-to-state relations should
be based on the five principles of mutual respect for sovereignty
and territory integrity, none aggression, none interference of
each others' internal affairs, equality and mutual benefits, and
peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
And then countries should seek common prosperity by enhancing
economic cooperation, opening up markets to each other and
eliminating unequal and discriminatory policies in economic and
trade fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, countries should enhance mutual trust and
understanding through dialogue and cooperation and promise to
solve disputes and conflicts by peaceful means, he said,
</P>
<P>
Chi said security dialogues should be aimed at enhancing trust
instead of confrontation and should not endanger other countries'
security interests.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister emphasized that China does not pose a
military threat to the neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"In the past several years, some people in the world are
preaching "China threat" for ulterior motives," he said. "They are
trying to diplomatically alienate China from its neighboring
countries, to damage China's international image and hold up
China's development."
</P>
<P>
"Even if China becomes more developed and stronger, it will
never be a threat to any country in the world," Chi
said. "Instead, China will contribute to all mankind as a key
force to defend global peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
Chi arrived in Tokyo on Tuesday for a six-day visit, the first
official visit to Japan by a Chinese defense minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
