<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Automotive Industry Enters New Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 4 (Xinhua) -- After a decade of development,
the auto industry in Shanghai has entered a new period of
technological progress, a municipal government official told
Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Yu Guosheng, deputy director of the Municipal Economic
Commission, said that by the early years of the 21st century the
local automotive industry should be able to develop its own
products.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1960s, Shanghai first produced cars by imitating
Mercedes Benz products; in the early '80s, the city began to
manufacture Santana cars by cooperating with Germany's Volkswagen;
in the '90s, Shanghai Volkswagen developed the Santana 2000 cars
through a joint design with Volkswagen's overseas firms in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Shanghai has become the largest automotive
manufacturer in China. In 1997 the city turned out 230,000 Santana
cars with a 92 percent localization rate, which means that the
parts are made in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
According to Yu, Shanghai is now working with General Motors of
the United States to build the country's largest automotive
project. Once the project is completed, the city's car-making
capacity is expected to top 400,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's automotive industry, one of the six pillar
industries for the city, has broad prospects with the support from
both central and local governments, Yu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
