<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wolfensohn: World Bank Focuses on Crisis' Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Visiting World Bank President
James D. Wolfensohn said here Wednesday that the bank is focusing
its attention on efforts to manage the social impact of the
prolonged monetary crisis in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"One goal of the presence of the World Bank (here) is to assist
the government in overcoming the social impact of the prolonged
and ongoing economic crisis," Wolfensohn said during a discussion
with 70 public figures, including economists and non-governmental
organization activists. "There will be no stability and peace if
the people are not fed. There will also be no confidence to
restore the economy."
</P>
<P>
Social protection is badly needed to cushion the impact of the
crisis, he said, adding that preventing panic over food is an
important effort.
</P>
<P>
"Thus, the World Bank has provided assistance for a social
program which will be carried out soon," he said.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund has committed a 40 billion U.S.
dollar bailout package for Indonesia, some 4.5 billion dollars of
which will come from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank will release 2 billion dollars this year, to be used
for a program that will protect the poor against the impact of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn also said the bank wants to help in structural
reforms, especially in terms of banking supervision.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank chief, who arrived here Tuesday evening from
Kuala Lumpur for a three-day visit as part of a seven-day tour of
Southeast Asian countries, noted that the discussion aimed to seek
inputs from the Indonesians themselves on how to bail the country
out of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn will meet with Indonesian President Soeharto this
evening to discuss the monetary crisis in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
