<HEADLINE> Liaoning Reports Comprehensive Rural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning Province, a major
agricultural base in northeast China, recorded good agricultural
harvests in 1997 despite severe droughts in many areas.
</P>
<P>
The province harvested some 13 million tons of grain in 1997,
with its total output non-stable foodstuffs such as vegetables,
meat, eggs, milk and aquatic products exceeding 20 million
tons. The annual per capita income of farmers hit 2,350 yuan,
according to a local agriculture official.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the good harvest to large scale irrigation
projects and reinstatement of the land contract system for farming
households.
</P>
<P>
Severe drought conditions affected more than 1.3 million ha
during 1997. The provincial government responded to the crisis by
allocating 200 million yuan to dig 10,000 wells to irrigate 46,600
hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
Rural industrial firms placed priority on the development of
agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning maintained strong comprehensive development despite the
fact that acreage sown to grain crops fell by three percent on the
1990 level. The output value of forestry, animal husbandry,
side-line products and fisheries sectors currently accounts for 50
percent of Liaoning's total agricultural output value.  
</P>
</TEXT>
