<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Banks Enjoy Healthy Profit Growth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's banking sector
enjoyed healthy profit growth in 1997 but faces a tougher year in
1998, acting chief executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority
(HKMA) David Carse said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The driving forces behind the satisfactory performance last
year were "strong volume growth in domestic lending and generally
good asset quality," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, profits were affected by the narrowing of margins in
the second half of 1997, particularly following the rise in the
Hong Kong Inter-bank Offered Rate from October, he said.
</P>
<P>
While predicting 1998 to be a "tougher year", Carse also
stressed: "Banks have budgeted for reasonable profits in 1998 and
all the banks are expected to make money."
</P>
<P>
Although bad debts are expected to rise this year, there are a
number of mitigating factors -- banks are starting 1998 with good
asset quality, bad debt provisions remain relatively low, banks
are not over-exposed to regional economies, and the quality of
bank management in Hong Kong is good, he said.
</P>
<P>
Loans overdue for more than three months and rescheduled
amounted to 20.2 billion HK dollars (2.6 billion U.S. dollars) at
the September of 1997, occupying a relatively low level of 1.83
percent of total loans.
</P>
<P>
The HKMA will take measures to avoid undue property
concentration, he added. Property exposures at the end of December
1997 took account of 44.2 percent of loans for use in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"Banks whose exposure is above the industry average of about 40
percent should stabilize or reduce that percentage, however, it is
unrealistic to expect all banks to get down to 40 percent in the
short term," Carse noted.
</P>
<P>
"Local banks have adopted a more cautious attitude toward
property lending" since the regional financial turmoil hit Hong
Kong in October, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides monitoring property exposures, the HKMA will continue
to promote sound fundamentals in local banks in 1998: capital
adequacy, liquidity, loan to deposit ratio and sound risk
management, Carse said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali King Calls Special Parliament Session, Ending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The political uncertainty in
Nepal ended Wednesday as King Birendra finally chose to accept the
submission by 96 MPs to convene a special session of parliament on
February 11 to discuss their no-confidence motion against the
present government.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra decided to call the special session after taking
the Supreme Court's advice, though it is not a binding one.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa, who came to power last
October, now faces the censure motion, as his recommendation to
dissolve parliament and hold mid-term elections was turned down by
the King.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of crisis in the Himalayan kingdom is
political as well as constitutional.
</P>
<P>
The crisis emerged on January 8 when Prime Minister Thapa
recommended the King to dissolve parliament for fresh polls to
forestall the move by 96 MPs from the opposition Communist Party
of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) and his own National
Democratic Party (RPP) to file a censure motion against his
coalition government.
</P>
<P>
The country has witnessed four coalition governments since the
mid-term polls in late 1994. Thapa is just another victim of
coalition politics, and if anything, he is the most short-lived
one to face a censure motion.
</P>
<P>
For King Birendra, the headache is that the two recommendations
are both constitutional, and that the Supreme Court had previously
handed down two conflicting verdicts, making it really hard for
him to make a choice.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the court ruled that Prime Minister Girija Prasad
Koirala of the Nepali Congress (NC) was within his constitutional
authority to recommend dissolution of parliament for fresh polls.
</P>
<P>
But the following year it overturned the similar recommendation
made to the king by Prime Minister Man Mohan Adhikari of the
CPN-UML, ruling that dissolution was not allowed if an alternative
government could be formed from the existing parliament.
</P>
<P>
After days of consultations with advisors, legal experts and
party leaders, King Birendra still could not make a decision. He
referred the matter to the apex court on January 13.
</P>
<P>
But the King's move drew criticism as well. Some argued that
the King must consult with the prime minister before acting upon
anything except matters specifically reserved to his discretion.
The ruling NC and RPP both hit at the King's move.
</P>
<P>
During the week-long discussions held at the Supreme Court
beginning on January 19, party representatives and legal experts
stuck to their own arguments. The focus was on whether the prime
minister's recommendation should enjoy priority over that of the
MPs.
</P>
<P>
Though Prime Minister Thapa's recommendation gained the upper
hand in the discussions, the final say lies in the nine judges of
the court's special bench.
</P>
<P>
Six of them including the chief justice favored a special
session of parliament, while the other three voted for dissolution
of parliament for fresh polls.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the apex court's opinion would clear
confusion over the interpretation of some articles of the
constitution and set a guideline for future political practices.
</P>
<P>
Now the country's attention shifts to the upcoming session of
the Lower House. No one can predict exactly the fate of the
present government, yet it is safe to say that horse-trading, as
usual, will work its way right before the session opens.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0109 </DOCNO>
