<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation at 6.88 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's inflation rate in
January reached 6.88 percent, raising the average from April 1997
to January 1998 to 15.97 percent, or tripling the 4.24 percent
recorded over the same period in the previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
This was largely due to the rise in prices for clothing, food,
goods and services as well as for housing, Information Minister
Hartono said here Wednesday after a limited cabinet meeting
chaired by President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Industry and Trade Minister Tunky Ariwibowo said the
country's trade in November last year registered a 1.4 billion
U.S. dollar surplus, with 720 million dollars coming from
non-oil/gas commodities.
</P>
<P>
"For the past five years, there has been no surplus in the
trade of non-oil/gas commodities higher than 700 million U.S.
dollars. Only last November (did we get such a surplus)," the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
He noted however that oil/gas imports decreased from 468
million dollars in November 1996 to 243 million dollars in
November 1997 while total imports fell from 3.6 billion dollars to
3.2 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
