<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Improved in North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Massive infrastructure
construction in north China's Hebei Province last year greatly
improved the investment environment there, according to local
officials.
</P>
<P>
The province built 234 kilometers of new expressways in
1997. The one-way road between Shijiazhuang, the provincial
capital, and Anyang, an important city in neighboring Henan
province, and the road linking Tangshan with Tianjin and Jingtang
Harbor have opened to traffic.
</P>
<P>
Construction of expressways between Beijing and Shenyang and
between Baoding and Tianjin is in full swing.
</P>
<P>
Eight newly built berths at the Jingtang Harbor are
operational, bringing the harbor's annual handling capacity to 5
million tons.
</P>
<P>
The fourth-phase construction of a coal project at the
Qinhuangdao Port has been completed, making it the largest coal
transit center in China.
</P>
<P>
Expansion projects at the Shijiazhuang Airport made it possible
to open new routes to Hong Kong and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Telephone switchboards across the province have been expanded
by 720,000 lines, bringing the telephone exchange capacity in
Hebei to 5.1 million, seventh in the country.
</P>
<P>
New generating units have been installed in six power plants
with an additional installed capacity of 1.34 million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
A provincial official said Hebei would build 152 key
infrastructure projects this year with a total investment of 103.9
billion yuan, which includes 1 billion U.S. dollars of foreign
funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
