<HEADLINE> Teenagers Report on Salt-Melted Snow's Environmental Impact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Two teen-age Beijing
schoolgirls have studied the effects of salt-melted snow on the
environment, offering scientific evidence for an environmental
protection regulation promulgated by the municipal government this
winter.
</P>
<P>
Clearing away the snow on the streets has been a headache for
the environmental department after every snowfall. To avoid
traffic accidents, they usually spray salt water on the streets to
speed up the melting process.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from the environmental department,
Beijing sprayed water containing about 600 tons of salt on the
city's main streets and highways after a heavy snowfall in
mid-January. Chemical examination showed that the content of salt
in the snow in some areas was about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Nan and Yang Jingjing, two schoolgirls in Beijing No.13
Middle School, found that street cleaners put the salt-melted snow
underneath the trees along the streets, and expressed concerns
about the possible adverse effects on the trees.
</P>
<P>
The two girls collected soil samples under the trees along the
streets, and compared the samples with the soil in their
school. Their test showed that the content of salt in the soil
samples from the streets was much higher.
</P>
<P>
They also carried out an experiment, giving evidence that the
soil with a high salt content destroys plants cells, erodes the
roots and causes the leaves to wither.
</P>
<P>
After a year's investigation, the two girls presented their
report to the environmental protection department with a warning
that salt-melted snow is the main cause of increased salt in the
soil.
</P>
<P>
Related departments issued a regulation this winter forbidding
the piling up of salt-melted snow under the trees and in lawns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
