<HEADLINE> More S.Koreans Apply for Unemployment Benefits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 4 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,748 South Koreans
applied for unemployment benefits on Monday alone, the Labor
Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The figure showed the highest-ever application rate since the
nation began its unemployment insurance system in July, 1995.
</P>
<P>
With the employment situation worsening, statistics issued
by the ministry showed that 1,199 registered for unemployment
benefits every day last month.
</P>
<P>
The nation's labor force market is also heading towards
instability with supply well outstripping demand.
</P>
<P>
A new trend has surfaced in the country's labor market, every
100 job seekers, including laid-off collars, are competing for 77
jobs in 3D (dirty, difficulty and dangerous) sectors, which was
specially left for foreigners.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, one of "the Four Dragons in Asia," has been in
serious financial troubles caused by corporate failures and bad
loans of financial institutions since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with the International Monetary Fund
last December for rescue loans of 57 billion U.S. dollars, the
nation has to restructure its economy, completely open its
financial market, shut down its ailing financial institutions and
pay back a large part of its foreign debts of 153 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country also has to solve the issue of mass layoffs caused
by the forthcoming bankruptcy of medium and small-sized
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
