<HEADLINE> Manila Pledges Earlier Recovery of Crash Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
use all available resources to facilitate the earliest recovery of
the bodies of passengers and crew aboard the ill-fated Cebu
Pacific plane that crashed Monday in Mindanao, an official said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The DC-9 passenger plane carrying 104 people, including five
crew members, went missing Monday after it left Manila for the
southern city of Cagayan de Oro. The Philippine Air Force spotted
Tuesday afternoon the possible wreckage site off the northeastern
slope of Mt. Sumagaya in Misamis Oriental, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Josefina T. Lichauco, transportation and communication
secretary, told reporters here that the government will do its
best for the earlier recovery of the victims of the air disaster.
</P>
<P>
Lichauco also dismissed Tuesday's press reports about 15
survivors as inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
He said that when such reports came out, rescuers from the army
and the Air Transport Office of his department had not been able
to reach the site due to gusty winds.
</P>
<P>
The local press, citing local officials and police, said
Tuesday that rescuers had found 15 survivors and 30 dead bodies in
Mt. Sumagaya.
</P>
<P>
As of 11:30 Wednesday, Luchauco said, the ground rescue team
who left Tuesday were still six kilometers from the site. Rain
showers and strong gusty winds are making even the establishment
of a landing site difficult.
</P>
<P>
He said a number of pictures taken by the air force could
hardly show any substantial portion of the plane wreckage leading
to a tentative conclusion that an explosion could have happened.
</P>
<P>
But earlier in the day, rescuers found debris of the plane
spreading in areas around Mt. Sumagaya, including calling cards of
passengers, documents and a curtain of the plane.  
</P>
