<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Ambassador: Albright Brings Nothing to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright made no contribution to the Mideast peace process in her
recent regional tour, Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al
Kodra said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"She has brought nothing new to the Middle East peace process
and the Palestinian-Israeli differences were not resolved," al
Kodra told reporters at Arish Airport, 360 kilometers northeast of
Cairo, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after seeing off Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat, who was leaving for Spain
and the Netherlands to discuss Europe's role in the Middle East
and financial assistance to the PNA, the MENA said.
</P>
<P>
Al Kodra said Arafat and Albright discussed specific ideas and
American proposals about the peace talks between the Palestinians
and the Israelis when she visited the Palestinian self-rule areas
last week.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinian side rejected the American proposals
because they ran counter to the Palestinian-Israeli agreements, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the U.S. proposed a step-by-step Israeli troop
pullback in the West Bank in parallel with the Palestinian
fulfillment of Israel's security demands.
</P>
<P>
"The American proposals only express the American and Israeli
viewpoints without lending any consideration to the Palestinian
side," the Palestinian Ambassador complained.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since last
March when Israel started a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as the capital of their
future independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
