<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Firmer Despite Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Australian shares closed
slightly firmer Wednesday despite a weaker resource sector, as
industrial stocks followed Wall Street higher.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries gained 2.5 points, or 0.9 percent, to
2,656.9 after the U.S. blue chip index, the Dow Jones industrial
average, finished 52.57 higher at 8,160.35.
</P>
<P>
A broker from a domestic firm said the market had been calm, if
not quiet.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think anybody has been too fussed about the Asian
markets today," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 3.7 points, or 0.31 percent, to
1,182.1 while the all industrials index was up 9.3 points, or 0.21
percent, to 4,513.0.
BDH182WSW002S04PEQL19:5119:532596
</P>
<P>
The gains in the industrial sector were led by a sharp rise in
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp, whose stocks were lifted 31 cents to
9.02 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks closed weaker, retracing some of their
spectacular gains in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank fell 15 cents, ANZ fell six,
Commonwealth Bank finished down seven and Westpac fell 0.3 cents.
</P>
<P>
But it was St George Bank shares which grabbed the attention of
brokers Wednesday, as commentators speculated that National
Australia Bank wants to sell its near six percent stake.
</P>
<P>
St George shares closed down 23 cents on relatively light
turnover of 792,385 shares.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, gold plunged through 300 U.S. dollars an ounce
overnight to open in Sydney at 295.35 an ounce. It closed here at
296.75. Brokers said that the precious metal had not had the
fundamental support for its recent push up through the crucial
300-mark.
</P>
<P>
Despite a rise in the price of base metals, mining giant BHP
fell three cents, Rio Tinto also lost three and WMC gained eight.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 261.03 million Shares, valued at 754.76
million Australian dollars (513.23 million US dollars) with falls
outnumbering rises 593 to 504.  
</P>
