<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weaker on Retail Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar weakened
Wednesday while the domestic bond market rallied following the
release of weaker-than-expected retail sales figures.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed at 67.92 US cents, well down from
68.62 locally late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It began the day half a U.S. cent weaker, dragged down by an
overnight slump in the price of gold.
</P>
<P>
In the U.S., COMEX gold for current delivery closed at 295.80
US dollars per ounce, down 7.60 from the previous close.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was then sold off further after the
Australian Bureau of Statistics announced that retail turnover
fell 0.8 percent, seasonally adjusted, to 11.143 billion
Australian dollars (7.577 billion US dollars) in December.
</P>
<P>
Following reports of bumper Christmas sales, an increase of 1.0
percent in retail trade had been widely expected.
</P>
<P>
"The market was stunned by the weakness in retail trade for
December, given the unequivocally strong anecdotal evidence,"
Societe Generale chief economist Glenn Maguire said.
</P>
<P>
"The market consensus had been that consumers were cashed up
and spending strongly in the pre-Christmas period," he said.
</P>
<P>
St George Bank foreign exchange trading manager Stuart Moore
said the Australian dollar fell to 67.80 US cents on the news.
</P>
<P>
However, buying by US names kept that level supported, and the
Australian dollar bounced back to 68.10 during the session.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished the session at 85.23 yen, down
from 86.50 here Tuesday, and at 1.2338 marks down from 1.2459.
</P>
</TEXT>
