<HEADLINE> China Adopts Measures to Protect Loulan Site in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, February 4 (Xinhua) -- China has introduced a series of
measures to protect Loulan, an ancient city which prospered on the
legendary "Silk Road" over 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
A cement stele bearing the words "a major historical and
cultural site under state protection" and a brief introduction of
the city was recently erected at the Loulan site in the Lop Nur
region in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
"We delimited the protected area and anyone illegally entering
the area or damaging the ancient site will be severely punished,"
according to Yue Feng, director of the Xinjiang Cultural Relics
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Loulan, one of the busiest commercial cities on the ancient
"Silk Road", served as a transportation hub for the flow of goods
from China to the western world. Shifting desert sand mysteriously
buried the city in the fourth century.
</P>
<P>
A Swedish archeologist discovered the ruins located close to
Lop Nur Lake in 1900. Thereafter, adventurers from Europe and
Japan flocked to the site and pilfered numerous cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
The Lop Nur Region was designated as China's nuclear testing
center in the 1960s, and unauthorized individuals were banned from
entering the area. The Chinese government agreed to the moratorium
on nuclear testing in 1996 and adventurers were once again allowed
to enter the area.
</P>
<P>
Yue noted that archeologists have scoured the Loulan site and
delimited a protected area covering some 30 square kilometers. A
centrally located Buddhist pagoda serves as the Loulan symbol.
</P>
<P>
"We've drafted a plan to renovate the ancient site and are
currently awaiting final approval from the State Bureau of
Cultural Relics," said Yue, adding that "the bureau has already
allocated 400,000 yuan (about 48,000 US dollars) to support the
project which will be completed at a total cost of dozens of
million yuan."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Research Nuclear Reactor Inaugurated in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
and his Argentine counterpart Carlos Menem inaugurated Egypt's
second research nuclear reactor that was built in cooperation with
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the new nuclear reactor in Inshass on the
northeastern skirts of Cairo is the focus of the one-day visit of
the Argentine president who arrived here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The 22-megawatt reactor has medical, industrial and
agricultural applications.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak delivered a speech at the inauguration in which he
lauded the Egyptian-Argentine cooperation in scientific and
technological domains as "an example of fruitful south-south
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
He reviewed Egypt's efforts in peaceful usage of nuclear
technology, emphasizing that Egypt exposes all its installations
to international surveillance.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Mubarak and Menem will hold a session of talks later
in the day on bilateral relations and issues of mutual concern,
including the Iraqi crisis over U.N. weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying Menem is Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella, who was
quoted by Argentine media on Sunday as saying Argentina was ready
to join any military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During the president's short stay in Cairo, the two sides will
sign a number of cooperation agreements in the technical and
scientific, security fields, as well two private sector
agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
