<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts Measures to Protect Loulan Site in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A two-ton stele, which stands 1.8 meters in height and has a
width of one meter, stands beside the east gate leading to the
ancient city. Craftsmen erected the structure with the front side
facing east in order to protect it from strong northwesterly winds.
</P>
<P>
"The stele should have been built in 1982 when the site was
designated as a major historical and cultural site under state
protection," Yue said. "However, the work was delayed due to the
fact the site is surrounded by wastelands and desert," he added.
</P>
<P>
A team of twelve people, led by Yue, crossed a 300 km. stretch
of wastelands in six days to transport the stele to the site.
</P>
<P>
"Erecting the stele was a necessity," said Yue, adding that, "a
permanent symbol clearly delimiting the protected area will help
prevent illegal entries."
</P>
<P>
Several hundred geologists are currently exploring the Lop Nur
Region for oil and sylvite. Yue stressed that cultural relics
protection should be strictly enforced for all related
construction projects.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the increasing number of visitors to the
region has resulted in damage to come cultural relics. Yue's team
has removed over 300 kg of beverage containers and food boxes
discarded by people entering the area illegally. Yue said the team
burned some trash and buried the remainder some 30 km away from
the ancient site.
</P>
<P>
"Loulan has emerged as a hot topic in research related to the
Silk Road," Yue said, adding that "Protecting the site will
guarantee the success of ensuing archeological research." 
</P>
</TEXT>
