<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia, DPRK Sign Investment Guarantee Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) signed here Wednesday
an agreement on investment guarantee.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Secretary General Asmat Kamaluddin of
the Malaysian Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI)
and DPRK Ambassador to Malaysia Kim Jin Ok, provides the framework
for further expanding the flow of investments and business
activities between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Investments made by citizens of the two countries shall receive
treatment which is fair and equitable and not less favorable than
that accorded to those made by people of any third state, an MITI
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will protect investment by investors of both
countries made prior to as well as after the signing of the
agreement, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The accord provides certainties and addresses the concerns of
investors on matters pertaining to expropriation and
nationalization and repatriation of profits in terms of free
transfer of income accruing to investments.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for the settlement of investment disputes
through relevant international organizations such as the
International Center for Settlement of Investment Disputes.
</P>
<P>
So far, there has been no Malaysian investment in the DPRK and
vice versa.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between the two countries between January and
November 1997 amounted to 9.4 million ringgit (about 2.35 million
U.S. dollars), compared with 14.4 million ringgit (about 3.6
million dollars at the present rate) a year earlier.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
