<HEADLINE> Angola Detains Another S. African Cargo Plane </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- One more plane was detained
Tuesday at Luanda International Airport for transporting cargo
for the former rebel movement -- the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The "Antonov-26" transport plane, according to a report by
Angola News Agency Wednesday, belongs to Ukraine. It took off in
South Africa for Luanda with five Ukraine crew on board and two
South African passengers.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the detainment, said the report, is that it had
flown into the UNITA-occupied regions many times, transporting
cargoes for UNITA. For this the plane numbered "UR-260160" has
been put on the list of violating Angola's territorial space by
U.N observers in Angola.
</P>
<P>
But Victor Ferreira, an Angolan civil Aviation Bureau
official was quoted as saying that the Ukrainian plane got the
green light from his bureau, and the reason for its Detention was
to probe its past records of transporting cargoes for UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The plane, in service of South Africa's "SG Corporation", is
said to be carrying cargoes for Jamaca Civil Construction Company
Ltd in Angola.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time Angola detained a foreign plane. On
January 20, a South African DC-4 plane was forced to land by
Angolan airforce jets when it intruded into Angola's air space to
carry building materials for UNITA. Three crew and five
passengers aboard were detained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
