<HEADLINE> 25 Million Pak Children to Be Immunized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will launch the
second round of the World Health Organization-sponsored polio day
campaign on February 9 to immunize more than 25 million children
all over the country against the crippling disease.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth year of large-scale polio vaccination
campaign launched by the Pakistani government.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, there were 1,800 cases of polio in Pakistan. But two
years after the anti-polio vaccination campaign, the polio cases
were reduced to about 36, officials from the Health Ministry said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to get at least 25 million children
immunized during the second round of the polio day campaign.
</P>
<P>
Only 56 percent of the children in selected districts have
completed their routine immunization series. This means that many
children need to be immunized against polio, said officials for
the polio eradication program.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani government has been campaigning for the
immunization on radio and television besides observing special
days for the polio vaccination program to create awareness among
the people.
</P>
<P>
According to the District Health Office of Islamabad, a total
of 400 special polio centers in the 12 union councils of Islamabad
will administer oral polio vaccination on February 9.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Delegation Arrives for Nagano Winter Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese sports delegation for
the 18th Olympic Winter Games arrived here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese contingent, which was composed of 61 skaters and
skiiers, will take part in seven sports of speed skating, short-track
speed skating, figure skating, women's ice hockey, free style skiing,
cross country skiing and women's biathlon.
</P>
<P>
It is the sixth time that China take part in the Winter Olympics
since 1980, when Chinese athletes made their debut in Lake Placid, the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Xu Yinsheng, Chief-de-Mission of the Chinese delegation, would not
put his eyes on any gold medal this time. "We do not have any big
chances to win a gold medal at in Winter Olympics although we have a
desire to make a breakthrough in the last Winter Olympics of this
century," he said upon arrival.
</P>
<P>
"We would take this opportunity to learn from our rivals," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Among the 61 Chinese Olympians, 10 took part in the last Olympics
in Lillehammer, Norway four years ago when China picked up one silver
and two bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Chinese figure skater Chen Lu, bronze medalist in the women's
singles event last time, is the only medal winner who returns to the
ice rink this time.
</P>
<P>
But it would be difficult for Chen to find back her form in Nagano.
At the 1997 World Championships, she only finished 25th and had to win
an Olympic spot through qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
China would pin its medal hope on women's short track speed skating
and free style skiing. At the 1997 World Championships, Yang Yang
from Jilin Province in northeast China, collected titles in the
women's 500m, 1,000m and al-around events and Guo Dandan claimed the
first world title in the World Free Style Skiing Championships in
August last year.
</P>
<P>
"I will try to ski to my best and win a medal here in Nagano, " Guo
Dandan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
