<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM Accuses US of "Avarice" in Asia Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard Wednesday warned of a possible trade war with the United
States, accusing Washington of using the Asian financial crisis to
try to steal Australian export markets.
</P>
<P>
Howard made the charge as he announced federal assistance for
Australian exports to Indonesia to counter what he called
"avaricious competition" from the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Howard also said Australia was considering other steps to
protest against U.S. attempts to take advantage of the economic
upheaval in Asia to push the interests of their exporters.
</P>
<P>
"Our exporters are facing fierce, even on occasion actively
avaricious competition from United States exporters into
Indonesia, who are not being shy in the export methods being
employed in order to gain access to the Indonesian market," Howard
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He hinted that Australia was considering taking the U.S. to the
World Trade Organization (WTO), saying: "We're gathering material
about what is happening, let me put it that way."
</P>
<P>
The assistance Howard announced Wednesday will take the form of
short-term credit insurance through Australia's Export Finance and
Insurance Corporation (EFIC).
</P>
<P>
No figure has yet been put on the Indonesian package, which
will be made on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
Both Howard and Primary Industries Minister John Anderson have
criticized the U.S. for offering cash-strapped nations billion
dollar credit guarantees to bolster its exports.
</P>
<P>
However, a senior U.S. government official in Canberra for a
commodities conference Wednesday rejected the accusation by
Australia and played down the risk of a trade war with Australia.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) Agency Administrator
Susan Offutt said export guarantees, in which the government picks
up the tab for defaulted export payments, were a necessary tool.
</P>
<P>
"In our view the use of exports credit essentially introduces
stability into our market share at a time of financial
instability," Offutt told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"In any event we expect Australian exports of beef into the
region to expand at our expense because of the (Australian dollar)
currency devaluation."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
