<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Lanka Marks Golden Jubilee Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka held a grand ceremony
in front of the parliamentary complex in the suburbs of Colombo
Wednesday to mark the 50th Independence Day of the country amid
tight security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga, Prime Minister
Sirimavo Bandaranaike, cabinet ministers, Britain's Prince
Charles, foreign ministers and special envoys of 14 countries, as
well as foreign diplomats accredited to Sri Lanka attended the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In her speech to the nation, Kumaratunga urged the people to
pluck up their courage, fortitude and vision to bring harmony and
peace to the country.
</P>
<P>
She vowed to end the ethnic strife, which started in 1983,
while defending the territorial integrity of her country.
</P>
<P>
"We must proceed with fortitude to face the daunting challenges
of terrorism and the political and social violence," she said.
</P>
<P>
On arrival at the ceremony venue, the president hoisted a
national flag. It was followed by the singing of the national
anthem by a group of school girls.
</P>
<P>
After that, all the participants observed two minutes' silence
in honor of those patriots who have laid down their lives for the
freedom, unity, sovereignty and territorial integrity of Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony came to its climax when a military parade by the
armed forces and a procession of floats were held.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations were held amid extremely tight security. All
the main roads leading to the parliament were sealed off. Large
numbers of armed security personnel were guarding around the main
venue of celebrations.
</P>
<P>
Local and foreign reporters and photographers were frisked and
their cameras, recorders and cellular phones thoroughly examined
before they were allowed to enter the high security zone of the
parliamentary complex.
</P>
<P>
The main function had been scheduled to be held in Kandy, the
ancient capital some 115 km east of Colombo. However, after a bomb
attack by the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam in the city on
January 25, the government decided to shift the celebrations from
Kandy to Colombo just one week before the Golden Jubilee day.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was only part of the celebration activities to be
held in Sri Lanka these days. On Thursday, a grand exhibition
featuring the country's political, economic and social
achievements in the years after its independence from Britain will
be held in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Apart from that, scores of government or mass organizations are
going to hold various activities to mark the event. In the mean
time, the LTTE is believed to be doing their best to mar the day.
</P>
<P>
The three services of the armed forces and the police forces
are on high alert to preempt any sabotage.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
