<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Parties Meet on Transition Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's five political parties
met in the capital Abuja Tuesday on key issues on the country's
transition to civil rule.
</P>
<P>
But the parties refused to let their decisions known by the
public.
</P>
<P>
Justice Mamman Nasir, Chairman of the Transition
Implementation Committee (TIC), who was asked by the parties to
brief the press after the meeting, said the parties prefer to
consulting with the Head of State General Sani Abacha before making
their resolutions public.
</P>
<P>
"We are in a phase of development of this nation that is very
delicate," he said, adding that things must be done with care to
ensure peace and stability in the entire nation.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports said that the parties may have agreed to
adopt Sani Abacha as their consensus candidate in the
presidential elections scheduled for august 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
They also recommended that the national assembly election
scheduled for April be shifted to August 1, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Despite objections from the United Nigeria Congress Party
(UNCP) which saw a landslide victory in last December's state
house of assembly election, reports said, the parties may have
agreed to cancel the results of that election on the ground of
massive rigging.
</P>
<P>
The party leaders will meet with Head of State General Abacha
as soon as possible to discuss him with resolutions reached at
Tuesday's meeting, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
Speculations of the five parties adopting Abacha as their
consensus candidate have been wild as only Alhaji Mohammed Dikko
Yusuf, a former police chief, has declared his interest to
contest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Punch, a leading Nigerian newspaper today
quoted Eforo, a member of the TIC as saying that if Abacha is
adopted as the consensus candidate, a national referendum will
replace the presidential elections on August 1.
</P>
<P>
Upon receiving a formal letter from the parties, the TIC will
refer the matter with the Provisional Ruling Council (PRC), the
country's highest decision-making body for ratification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
