<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali King Decides to Call Special Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The month-old political
uncertainty in Nepal ended Wednesday as King Birendra decided to
accept the request by 96 MPs to convene a special session of
parliament to discuss their no-confidence motion against the
present government, Radio Nepal said.
</P>
<P>
The special session of parliament will be called for February
11, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The King made the decision in accordance with the Supreme
Court's advice.
</P>
<P>
Now Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa has to face the censure
motion against him barely four months after he came to power, as
his recommendation to dissolve parliament and hold mid-term
elections was turned down by the King.
</P>
<P>
The 96 MPs from the main opposition Communist Party of Nepal
(United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) and Thapa's own National
Democratic Party (RPP) had planned the censure motion in early
January, prompting Thapa to take his own preemptive move.
</P>
<P>
However, King Birendra still could not make a decision after
days of consultations with advisers, legal experts and party
leaders, and he referred the matter to the Supreme Court on
January 13.
</P>
<P>
The case is a delicate one for the court as well, as
recommendations by the prime minister and the MPs are both
constitutional. And what made it more complicated is that the
court had before handed down two conflicting verdicts.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, it ruled that Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala of
the Nepali Congress was within his constitutional authority to
recommend dissolution of parliament for fresh polls.
</P>
<P>
However, the following year it overturned the similar
recommendation made to King Birendra by Prime Minister Man Mohan
Adhikari of the CPN-UML, ruling that dissolution was not allowed
if an alternative government could be formed from the existing
parliament.
</P>
<P>
This time, the court invited party representatives and legal
experts to participate in the week-long discussions which began on
January 19. Prime Minister Thapa's recommendation gained the upper
hand in the discussions. But the nine-member special bench of the
court has the final say.
</P>
<P>
Six of the nine judges including the chief justice favored a
special session of parliament, while the other three voted for
dissolution of parliament for fresh polls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
