<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 10:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Slams US, Britain for Military Option </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) has
criticized the United States and Britain for threatening to take
military actions against Iraq, the Egyptian Gazette reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The possible use of force by the U.S. and Britain will cause
tension in the Middle East and damage the Arab national security,
AL Secretary General Ahmed Esmat Abdel-Meguid told reporters
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after briefing the representatives of the
22 members of the Arab League in Cairo on the purpose of his trip
to Baghdad Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his visit, he would meet Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein and try to persuade him to "avert a catastrophe."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred the arms inspectors of the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction from searching presidential palaces
suspected of hiding the banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has threatened to force Iraq to grant free access to
the UNSCOM through military action, which is staunchly supported
by Britain.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, many Arab countries joined the U.S.-led coalition
forces to drive Iraq out of Kuwait. But most of them today show
sympathy for the Iraqi people suffering from nearly eight-year-old
U.N. sanctions, and call for maintaining Iraq's security and
sovereignty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
