<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks Turkey's Support for Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
sought Turkey's support in case Washington launches a military
strike against Iraq, local daily Milliyet reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said that Clinton made known his position in a letter
conveyed to his Turkish counterpart Suleyman Demirel by
U.S. Ambassador to Turkey Marc Parris Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the U.S.-Turkish friendship is based on "the
two countries' solidarity in the Gulf region," adding that whether
this relationship will continue depends on Turkey's attitude.
</P>
<P>
The letter came as the U.S.-Iraqi stand-off worsened because
Iraq banned U.N. arms inspectors from inspecting presidential
palaces and Turkey called for a peaceful solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Clinton briefed Demirel on the U.S. stand concerning the Iraqi
cisis, saying that there are indications that diplomatic channels
could not put an end to the current situation.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that Clinton is sending a message to Ankara
that the U.S. government is determined to resort to force against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that former U.S. president George Bush
had earlier reminded Clinton that he should consult Turkey if a
military operation is needed to be carried out against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
As an important ally of the Western world, Turkey extended
full support to the U.S.-led multinational troops during the 1991
Gulf War which erupted following the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry officials said that the U.S. had
not made any request for using the Incirlik air base in Adana,
southern Turkey, which was used during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem is to arrive in Baghdad
late Wednesday. He will meet Iraqi leaderers on Thursday to
exchange views over the tensions.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of his visit to the Iraqi capital is to
clarify Turkey's attitude toward the current crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
