<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- New revelations on the French oil group Elf-Aquitaine show
that during the civil war in Congo Republic last year, the banking
establishment Fiba, which is controlled by Elf and Gabonese
President Omar Bongo, served as a behind-the-scene intermediary
between former president Pascal Lissouba and arms traffickers.
Created in the 1970s, Fiba handles millions of petrol dollar in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
-- The handling of the Iraqi crisis by the western allies give
the impression of of a great mess. While the United States
ambassador to the United Nations Bill Richardson said the diplomacy
was ``running out of steam,'' France and Russia still believe in the
usefulness of talks, with each of them sending envoys to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The closing of the Superphenix nuclear center by the French
government has provoked a creaking within the leftwing majority,
while the opposition rightwing denounced it as an ``electoral
manoeuvre'' aimed at the regional and cantonal elections to be held
next month. The French Communist Party condemned ``with all
clearness'' the closing of Superphenix ``in the name of independence
of energy'' of France.
</P>
<P>
-- The Paris Police Department asked Parisians not to borrow
vehicles and use public transport Wednesday to lower the level of
air pollution which has attained level two in the capital. The speed
of automobiles is also being limited and anti-pollution measures
reinforced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
