<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Cabinet Minister Leaves for Gulf Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Minister of State
for Cabinet Affairs and acting Foreign Minister Abdul Aziz Dakhil
Al-Dakhil left here Wednesday for Qatar starting a tour of Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) states.
</P>
<P>
An official at the Kuwaiti Foreign Ministry was quoted by the
Kuwaiti News Agency as saying that the tour stemmed from Kuwait's
desire to coordinate with its Gulf allies regarding the crisis of
weapons inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred the inspectors of the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction from searching presidential palaces suspected of
hiding banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to take military actions to
force Iraq to grant free access to the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti official said that during the tour, Al-Dakhil will
deliver letters to the leaders of the GCC states from Kuwaiti Emir
Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said Kuwait is to explain its position on the
need to compel Baghdad to comply with the U.N. Security Council
resolutions and destroy its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq invaded its neighbor Kuwait in August 1990, but was driven
out by the U.S.-led multi-nation forces in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has taken precautions, including raising the level of
readiness of the armed forces, to ward off Iraqi retaliation for
possible U.S. military actions.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf Cooperation Council, a regional political, economic
and military alliance, groups Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Qatar, the
United Arab Emirates, Oman and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
