<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Accelerates Development of Animal Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The output value of the
animal husbandry sector in Henan Province, a leading agricultural
producer in central China, has grown by an average annual rate of
25 percent over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate outstripped the national average by 10
percent. The 1997 output value of the animal husbandry sector
accounted for 35.6 percent of Henan's total agricultural output,
up 14 percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Some 489,000 households specialize in raising poultry and
domestic animals, a 10-fold increase on 1990. Said households
accounted 12.4 percent of the total number of live pigs sent to
slaughterhouses during the year, as well as 34.5 percent of the
total volume of poultry.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of animal husbandry in recent years has
enabled Henan's per capita consumption of meat and eggs to surpass
the national average, according to a local official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
