<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Renews Trade Risk Insurance for S. Korea, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 4 (Xinhua) -- As a result of the improved
prospects of economic stability in Southeast Asia, Israel has
decided to renew the government-backed foreign trade-risk
insurance to Thailand and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The 75 million U.S. dollars in insurance against political and
commercial risk offered by the Israel Foreign Trade Risk
Insurance Company was halted about six weeks ago, The Jerusalem
Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The situation was unclear regarding the area. Today, there
are much better indications, following the debt arrangements
reached with the Word Bank and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) for South Korea and Thailand," head of the insurance
company Doron Klausner said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The World Band and the IMF have arranged a 60 billion dollars
bailout for South Korea and 17.2 billion dollars for
Thailand. "We believe those countries will be able to meet
commitments," Klausner said.
</P>
<P>
Shahar Meidan, business development manager at the Tel Aviv
office of Nissho Iwai, Japan's sixth largest conglomerate, said
the renewal of the insurance will help Israeli companies feel
more secure about doing business in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
"One of the biggest problems with the Southeast Asian crisis
is the psychological effect. The renewal of insurance doesn't
make it more worthwhile, but increases the security of Israeli
companies," said Meidan.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that the Asia situation will have an affect
on Israeli industry. Israeli companies will now invest more in
other markets, including Japan which is not suffering much from
the crisis and Europe and the U.S.." he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
