<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mine Gas Explosion Claims Another Victim </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, February 4 (Xinhua) -- A miner seriously injured in a
recent gas explosion at a northeastern China coal mine died today
in a local hospital, bringing the total death toll to 78.
</P>
<P>
The gas explosion erupted at the state-owned Wangjiaying Coal
Mine in Liaoning Province on the evening of January 24, killing 77
at that time, injuring eight other miners.
</P>
<P>
Local officials noted that the gas explosion was the worst in
Liaoning's coal mines over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Vice Governor Chen Zhenggao said that life and production in
Wangjiaying have basically returned to normal, and that the cause
of the accident is still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Governor Zhang Guoguang urged all mines to draw a
lesson from the explosion and intensify mine safety efforts at a
tele-conference the following day.
</P>
<P>
Wangjiaying, a medium-sized mine in western Liaoning, began
coal cutting in 1987 and has a designed annual production capacity
of 1.2 million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
