<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovakia's Foreign Debt Hits New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia's foreign debt jumped
to a five-year record of 10.3 billion U.S. dollars last October,
according to Slovakia's National Bank Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It now accounts for 55 percent of the country's gross domestic
product, well above the "alarming level" of 40 percent, the bank
report shows.
</P>
<P>
In 1993 when it gained independence, Slovakia reported a
foreign debt of less than three billion dollars. The figure has
risen 2.5 fold in five years.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debt, which now stands at 1,937 dollars per capita, has
become a heavy burden for Slovakia's economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Threatens Northeastern Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Drought has been listed as one
of the major environmental factors threatening farming in the
northeastern Nigeria, the Daily Times quoted a biologist as
reporting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Most affected are the states of Borno, Yobe and Bauchi,
said Marths Verinumbe, a lecturer in the department of
biological sciences at the University of Maiduguri at a recent
seminar.
</P>
<P>
She said land degradation, reduction in land productivity and
income as well as loss of livelihood were the direct effect of
low rainfall, sparse vegetation, increased soil erosion and
decreased soil fertility.
</P>
<P>
The problem, she said, had also affected water supply for
domestic and agricultural needs, reduced the socio-economic
development and well-being of the people as well as depleting
plant and wildlife resources, which often led to reduction in
food, income and recreation.
</P>
<P>
The cutting of trees for fuel-wood and construction,
collection of other non-timber forest products such as gum,
fruits, nuts, vegetables and seeds as well as the massive
clearing of lands for farming activities contributed
significantly to environmental degradation.
</P>
<P>
The lecturer recommended, among other things, the government
provide alternative grazing areas to reduce the demand pressure
on trees as well as raise public awareness with respect to the
maintenance or sustainability of scarce forest resources.
</P>
<P>
According to other researchers, the major causes of the
environmental problem in northeastern Nigeria include
desertification which leads to prolonged droughts, poor water
resources management, wind erosion, deforestation and land
degradation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jewish Housing Plan in East Jerusalem Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Interior Ministry
has given the final approval to the construction of 132 housing
units for Jewish settlers in the controversial Ras Amud Arab
neighborhood in East Jerusalem, Israel Radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The plan submitted by Jewish millionaire Irving Moscowitz of
the United States was published in the government gazette, the
radio said, adding that another plan to build 500 homes for Arabs
in the area was also agreed by the ministry and published in the
gazette.
</P>
<P>
Moscowitz reportedly bought a plot in the Arab neighborhood
more than a decade ago, on which he has intended to build a Jewish
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Last September, the Interior Ministry rejected two appeals
against the construction of the settlement filed by two leftist
city councillors, clearing a major obstacle to the project.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu blocked the start
of the construction, citing concerns about sparking widespread
Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
To press their calls to start the construction, four rightist
Jewish families moved into two houses bought by Moscowitz on
September 14 last year, triggering strong protests from the
Palestinians and Israeli peace activists.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal with the government, the settlers were late
evacuated and replaced by a group of religious Jewish students.
</P>
<P>
Despite the approval by the Interior Ministry, the Israeli
government is unlikely to start the construction of the housing
units in Ras Amud Arab neighborhood at the moment to avoid
Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
An aide for Netanyahu was quoted by the radio as saying that
the government has means to stop the project.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority has blasted the Ras Amud
project as part of Israel's attempt to judaize Arab East Jerusalem
which was occupied by Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want East Jerusalem as the capital of their
future independent state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
