<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 08:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Foreign Exchange Reserves Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese gross foreign exchange
reserves rose 108 million U.S. dollars in January this year,
bringing the country's total reserves to 6.039 billion dollars,
local newspaper the Beirut Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted a central bank source as saying that the renewed
faith in the Lebanese pound and increased swapping of dollars for
the local currency were the main reasons for the increase in
foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
The faith came following the deposits which were made by Gulf
countries at the Lebanese central bank in recent weeks, the
source added.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Kuwaiti government deposited 100 million
dollars at 5 percent interest for three years, while in
December, Saudi Arabia's National Commercial Bank deposited 500
million dollars at the same interest and for the same
duration.
</P>
<P>
Nabil Chaya, senior official of Lebanese leading bank Banque
Audi, said that the approval of the 1998 budget by parliament
last week had also boosted confidence locally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Comments on Domestic, World Affairs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng met
with China Information chairman Feng D, publisher Zhu Yongkang and
Editor-in-Chief Xu Jingen in Beijing on December 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Li answered their questions concerning the reform of
state-owned enterprises, democracy and the legal system, the
current world situation, Sino-U.S. relations, Sino-Japanese
relations, and other issues of interest.
</P>
<P>
Following is the full text of Li's interview with the monthly
English journal published in the United States:
</P>
<P>
China Information (CI): How much confidence does the Chinese
government have in the success of state-owned enterprise reform
and what special measures have been taken to prevent possible
setbacks?
</P>
<P>
Li Peng: First of all, we should make it clear that the
situation in China's state-owned enterprises is not as serious as
some Western media reports have made it seem. Some large
state-owned enterprises run well. The year 1997 witnessed major
reform in the state-owned enterprises and optimistic changes in
enterprise benefits. A group of large and mid-sized enterprises
have received support, and many enterprises and enterprise groups
have emerged with practical economic strength and vitality.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises are still the main tax payers in
China. There are certain difficulties faced by them, and that is
the reason for the reform. The direction is to establish a modern
enterprise system, change the management system, and turn these
enterprises into new entities that adopt a system of personal
responsibility for profit and loss and practice independent
management, clearly identify ownership, and separate
administration from these enterprises. We have good examples in
this respect. The problem is that some people worry about social
problems caused by more redundant workers following further
reform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
