<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Reaffirms Ban on Political Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda reaffirmed the ban on
political activities of various parties before referendum in
2,000, The New Vision reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Emmanuel Kerenga, State Minister for Justice and
Constitutional Affairs, said the ban will be lifted only if the
electors voted in favor of a multi-party system in the referendum
to be held in 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Kerenga made the announcement against the background that a
report carried by local paper The Monitor said political
activities will be lifted by June this year.
</P>
<P>
The Political Organisations Bill being drafted may relax or
tighten the restriction imposed on party activities, but the bill
will not lift the ban on political activities of parties, he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the the state minister, the next presidential and
parliament elections will be held in 2001 under a system which
the electorate of the country will vote for in the referendum.
But those advocating for multi-party system will be allowed to
start their campaigning in June 1,999, a year before the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni has reaffirmed that
multi-party system did not apply to Uganda. There is a prefeudal
social structure in the country, and introduction of a
multi-party system will lead to tribalism which will distabilize
the country, he underlined. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
