<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Comments on Domestic, World Affairs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li Peng: Years of reforms show us that once we have adequately
settled the relationships among reform, development and stability,
we can solve these problems as well. Development is our goal,
reform is the motive force, and stability is the condition.
</P>
<P>
We will readjust the reform each year according to the
practical conditions in the nation, so that the people and the
enterprises can bear the changes. Take reform in the price system
for instance. We have gradually lifted the control over prices year
by year, and now the prices of most commodities are controlled by
the market. But the prices of some key commodities that are
significant to the national economy and people's livelihood
remain under state control.
</P>
<P>
The reforms in state-owned enterprises are the same. We will
try to establish a modern enterprise system in most large and
mid-sized state-owned enterprises by the end of this century, but
this doesn't mean that the system should be established in all
such enterprises. We will make new progress in state-owned
enterprise reform with better economic benefits in 1998 by means
of reform, regrouping, renovation and the strengthening of
management according to different situations.
</P>
<P>
We have obtained a great deal of experience in solving such
problems. We will take into consideration the ability of the
people and the enterprises to bear the burdens of reform during
the whole process. We will quicken our steps if the conditions are
good and slow down if the conditions are not ripe. In short, we
will maintain continuous progress. We are quite confident in the
success of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Comments on Domestic, World Affairs (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li: We will further strengthen the work on the basis of our
achievements in democracy and legal system. The work is carried
out according to the actual situation in China, not according to
Western values. Conditions vary in different countries and so do
democracy and legal system. The United States adopts direct
elections. But actually, the selection is only between two
candidates. Still they claim it the greatest democracy. While in
China the people's congress system requires direct elections in
grass-roots units and indirect elections in the upper leadership
from 3,000 representatives. This represents different values and
different social conditions. The Westerners seem to be interested
in the recent direct elections in townships, which they don't
realize has been the practice in China for years.
</P>
<P>
Along with the deepening of reform, we will ensure the people
fully enjoy their rights as the masters of the country in
accordance with the Constitution, such as their supervision over
governmental work, criticizing the shortcomings in the government
work through the media and public opinion, and exposing corruption
in the society, so as to enable the people's congresses at all
levels to play a full role. The best standard is to satisfy the
Chinese public. We can learn something useful from the West, such
as news supervision. But our news criticism is different from
theirs. Our news reports are based on serious investigation to
ensure the fidelity of the news, which is obviously different from
some fake reporting for temporary or sensational efforts in the
Western news media. The supervision by our news media and public
opinion will be reinforced in the future.
</P>
<P>
In regard to human rights, we hold that there are different
points of view on this issue. The West stresses the human rights
of individuals. To them, the individual's human rights are supreme
and beyond the interests of the collectives and state, and cannot
be infringed at all. Still, even judging by their own standards,
the human rights situation in the West is not satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
China is a developing socialist country that had experienced a
semi-colonial and semi-feudal history. The Chinese people have
been liberated only after a long and unremitting struggle, which
means they have obtained great human rights. The next step is to
gain the rights to exist and to develop and then improve
individual human rights. We use the word "improve" because the
building of democracy and legal system in China is a process of
progressive and continuous completion and improvement, which
complies well with the actual condition of the country. It is
improper or unrealistic to judge China's democracy and legal
system and human rights condition by Western standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Comments on Domestic, World Affairs (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CI: The development of China has become a focus of media
reports since the 1990s. But the Westerners have a common worry
that a powerful China will prove a threat to regional
stability. During his visit to the United States, President Jiang
Zemin reiterated that China would never seek hegemony. How can we
convince the West of the truth of this stand?
</P>
<P>
Li: Your question reflects the fact that many Westerners don't
have a good understanding of China. China is the largest developing
country and has concentrated on the economic development. After
New China was founded, especially over the past two decades since
the reform and open policy were initiated, China's economy has
made rapid progress and national strength has reinforced. However,
with a population of more than 1.2 billion, and a poor foundation,
the per-capita GNP is still fairly low. When many foreigners come
to China, what they visit are merely developed cities of Shanghai,
Beijing and Shenzhen, but not the backward and poor central and
western regions. So they can't imagine that there are still 50
million Chinese living in poverty.
</P>
<P>
We have made a three-step strategy for development, the target
for the middle of the next century is to reach the level of
moderately-developed countries. It will take much longer to
reach levels as seen in the United States. To realize the
three-step development strategy and enhance the material and
cultural living standards of the people, on the one hand we need a
stable domestic political situation, and a peaceful international
environment on the other, especially a friendly
neighborhood. These are the preconditions for continuous
development in China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people know well the significance of peace and
stability, and China opposes hegemony and will never seek hegemony
or any sphere of influence. This is the solemn promise the Chinese
government has made to the whole world, and it has been determined
by the nature of our country. China will never be a threat to any
other country or region. Those who spread the myth of the "China
threat" have ulterior motives. The military force of China is for
defensive purposes only and "we will not attack unless we are
attacked."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Comments on Domestic, World Affairs (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CI: How does China view today's world order?
</P>
<P>
Li: Great changes have taken place in the world situation. The
trend toward a multi-polar situation is accelerating more
obviously than ever before. The concept of multi-polarity has been
accepted by more and more countries, and most people think
multi-polarity is better than single polarity and is beneficial to
the whole world. It is unimaginable that the whole world of some
200 countries and a population of more than 5 billion could be
ruled by one country. When observing the current world situation,
people have noticed that the relations between big powers are
being adjusted, economic and military safety elements have become
ever more prominent in international relations, and developing
countries are playing a significant role in promoting the
formation of a multi-polar situation and ending the irrational old
international political and economic orders. All these are
characteristics that should be noticed in the present-day
international situation.
</P>
<P>
China adheres to an independent and peaceful diplomatic policy
and seeks friendly neighbor relations. To be independent means not
to blindly follow others, but to have our own point of view on
world affairs and our own principles in viewing international or
regional disputes to make objective and just judgments on
particular issues.
</P>
<P>
A peaceful diplomacy ensures that all foreign diplomatic
actions will be beneficial to world peace because only under a
peaceful environment can development be realized. One of the most
important principles stuck to by the Chinese nation is a friendly
neighborhood and actively developing relations with neighboring
countries. Remarkable accomplishments have been achieved in this
regard in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Comments on Domestic, World Affairs (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CI: Fairly great improvements have been made in Sino-U.S. and
Sino-Japanese relations. President Jiang Zemin has visited the
United States and you have visited Japan. But there are still some
problems in Sino-U.S. and Sino-Japanese relations, what do you
think of the prospects for these relations?
</P>
<P>
Li: President Jiang Zemin paid a state visit to the United
States, which was the greatest event in China's foreign affairs in
1997. It was the first visit by a Chinese head-of-state to the
United States in the past 12 years and was a significant
breakthrough, marking an end to the West's unjust sanction against
China. The visit was a great success and helped strengthen mutual
understanding, and expand common ground for future cooperation. It
promoted Sino-U.S. relations, shifting to a new stage of
development.
</P>
<P>
We have all along taken Sino-U.S. relations
seriously. Naturally, the United States will hold one pole in a
multi-polar situation, and an important pole at that. China will
not underestimate the role played by the United States in the
world. There are many things we could learn from the United States
in economic strength, science, technology and culture. But we
could never agree to the U.S. claiming of "leadership over the
world" and I'm afraid that most countries in the world won't agree
to that.
</P>
<P>
We cannot tolerate U.S. interference in the internal affairs of
other countries. The United States always tries to place its
domestic laws beyond international laws and requires other
countries to abide by U.S. laws. This is the divergence between us
and the United States. But we have all along thought that there
are wide common interests between the two countries, which is the
foundation for mutual cooperation. We should try to seek common
ground while reserving differences, reduce conflicts and increase
dialogue to prevent contradictions and divergence from becoming
intensified.
</P>
<P>
From another point of view, the divergence between the United
States and China is partly because of a lack of mutual
understanding. In the mind of some U.S. senators we have spoken
with, China is still the backward image described in old movies or
novels, and they know very little about the present China, or what
they have heard is a pack of completely distorted facts. We hope
we can gain more mutual understanding and more common ground
through contacts and exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
