<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake City Discussing More Women Sports in 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Host for the 2002 Olympic
Winter Games Salt Lake City is considering to add more women sports in
their programme for the games.
</P>
<P>
The Salt Lake City Organizing Committee (SLOC) president Frank
Joklik said at a press conference here Wednesday afternoon that the
SLOC is discussing to include women's ski jumping, bob and luge at the
2002 Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"We'll work with the international federations to discuss what
additional sports may be considered for 2002," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the issue of new sports was underpinned by financial
considerations, but he explained adding more athletes -- such as women
-- to already existing facilities would not be impossible financially.
</P>
<P>
"There are financial considerations, but it is not like when a new
facility has to be built," he added.
</P>
<P>
Adding more sports might be an easy task for the SLOC, but winning
support of Utah citizens for the games could be difficult for the
organizers.
</P>
<P>
SLOC officials admitted that Utah citizens remain negative about
the 2002 games. "The perception among Utans is not what it should be,"
said SLOC media head Shelley Thomas. "We feel there's been a lot of
misinformation and misunderstanding. We have a big job ahead of us
getting the facts out in a more organized fashion than inthe past."
</P>
<P>
But she added SLOC had been making progress. "We've gone out of our
way to ensure we explain and spread message of the Olympics throughout
the state of Utah and I think we've made considerable progress," she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
