<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Comments on Domestic, World Affairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The core problem in Sino-Japanese relation is how to correctly
understand and regard Japan's invasion of China. We must eliminate
disturbance and settle the issue properly in order to develop
relations in a healthy way. The shadow caused by Japan's invasion
of China during World War II still exists today, and the
militarism and right-wing elements in Japan try to disturb and
destroy Sino-Japanese relations from time to time and some
Japanese politicians still do not hold a correct understanding of
the historical facts.
</P>
<P>
During my visit to Japan, I stressed time and again that it was
not the matter of Japan alone which road the nation takes, but a
matter of concern to Sino-Japanese relations and stability in the
neighborhood, and the world as well. After World War II, Japan
followed a peaceful road of development and achieved great
economic progress. It should continue to stick to the peaceful
development road, which will benefit Japan and win the nation the
trust of the people of Asia and the world, and it will bring more
common ground between our two countries. The youths in Japan today
know little of their history and they should be educated with
correct concepts of history if we are to realize generations of
friendship between our two countries.
</P>
<P>
Li summed up his remarks by saying the achievements made in
China's diplomatic work are based on those accomplished in
domestic work. He said the formal establishment of diplomatic
relations between China and South Africa is another great
achievement in China's diplomatic work. "Only after we have done
the domestic job well can we make more progress in diplomatic work
and our words on internations stages be taken seriously," the
premier added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
