<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Industry Witnesses Stable Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- China's automobile
manufacturing sector witnessed stable growth in terms of both
production and marketing in 1997, industry sources said.
</P>
<P>
The growth has been attributed to the fact that the sector
escaped the shackles of the planned economy and continued to
improve its structure and market exploration.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Motor Vehicles Department of the Ministry
of Machine-Building Industry show that state manufacturing
enterprises produced nearly 1.58 million motor vehicles and sold
1.56 million during 1997, up 7.37 percent and 7.82 percent on
1996, respectively. The sector's production-sales rate stood at
99.34 percent.
</P>
<P>
The sector's product mix witnessed significant improvement
during 1997, with the 481,600 units produced accounting for 30
percent of the nation's total output of motor vehicles. The
production figure represented a 24.22 percent rise on 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 474,200 automobiles sold during 1997 represented 22.88
percent growth on 1996. Santana model vehicles manufactured by
the Shanghai Volkswagen Corporation, a Sino-German joint venture,
led the nation in terms of both output and sales volume.
</P>
<P>
The Fukang model produced Citroen in central China's Hubei
Province, Auto (Aotuo) model by the Chang'an Company in Chongqing
and Jetta model by the First Automobile Works Corporation in Jilin
Province all witnessed expanding ranges in terms of both
production and marketing.
</P>
<P>
The annual growth rate for the production of mini-vans and
mini-buses has remained above 20.6 percent since 1990. A total of
156,000 mini-vans were produced in 1997, with the sales volume for
the year surpassing 160,000 units. Some 226,000 mini-buses were
produced and 212,400 units were sold during the year.
</P>
<P>
China produced 4,300 large buses in 1997, up 14.9 percent on
1996, with sales rising by 34.3 percent to 4,900 units. The
industry also produced and marketed some 31,000 heavy-duty trucks
during the year.
</P>
<P>
The auto industry's product mix has adapted to market changes,
with reduced production of medium-sized and light-weight trucks
and buses, both of which were formerly prime product categories
for the country's motor vehicle industry.
</P>
<P>
A total of 204,500 medium-sized and 477,100 light-weight motor
vehicles were produced in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The chaotic state affecting China's auto industry in recent
years has been brought under control along with the implementation
of development policies and improvements in the degree of
centralized production.
</P>
<P>
Each of 14 Chinese auto makers currently produce over 10,000
motor vehicles annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
