</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Gov't Banks Urged to Lower Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines is encouraging government banks to lead the way in
bringing down the high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said Wednesday that the
Monetary Board, the central bank's highest decision making body,
has urged these banks to take the first step toward achieving
lending rates acceptable to the public.
</P>
<P>
The country's government banks include Land Bank of the
Philippines, the Development Bank of the Philippines (DBP), the
Philippine National Bank and some other banks.
</P>
<P>
Singson explained that if this was successfully done, the
current interest rates could be reduced to between 20 to 21
percent.
</P>
<P>
If this happens, he said, commercial banks which are identified
to be imposing the high lending rates between 23 to 32 percent
could follow the trend later.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the central bank cannot force these banks to bring
down the interest rates because it is not implementable under the
present market situation wherein almost all the banks are using
the prevailing interest rates.
</P>
<P>
But the Monetary Board is finalizing a plan that would oblige
government lending agencies to take the lead in bringing down real
estate loans to as low as 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
High interest rates have been blamed for hampering corporations
from expanding business and worsening the effects of the currency
crisis on the economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
