<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Producer Inflation at 27-Year Low in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 4 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's producer
inflation dropped last month to its lowest level in almost 27
years, reinforcing forecasts of an interest rate cut as early as
next month.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year increase in the producer price index (PPI)
was four percent in December, the lowest since September 1971
when it was 3.7 percent, according to Central Statistical Service
figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The annualized PPI increase rate, which peaked at 9.6 percent
in March, was 4.7 percent in November.
</P>
<P>
The PPI rate in December fell below economists' forecast of
4.2 percent. The month-on-month rise between November and
December was a modest 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the PPI figure provided further evidence that
South Africa was winning the battle against inflation. Some
forecast an interest rate cut before the end of the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Africa's consumer inflation maintained a
downward trend for six consecutive months till December when it
fell to 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, what dampens hopes for the early easing of interest
rates was money supply increase, which was still well beyond the
central bank's target of 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
