<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Air Crash Kills Five </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 4 (Xinhua) -- A light aircraft
nose-dived into a coffee farm near the Arusha Airport in northern
Tanzania on Monday morning, killing the pilot and all four
foreign passengers.
</P>
<P>
The six-seater aircraft Cessna 207, belonging to a private
company Precision Air, crashed two minutes after it took off from
the airport, local media reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners include Italian nationals Ferry and his wife
Nobile, as well as Mohammed Hussein from Switzerland and
Szutenberg from Poland.
</P>
<P>
Their bodies, burnt beyond recognition, are lying at Mount
Meru Hospital mortuary in Arusha, said the Precision Air Branch
Manager for Arusha, Philemon Kisamo.
</P>
<P>
The plane, chartered by the four tourists, was flying towards
the Zanzibar isles. About two minutes after take-off at 7:50 am,
the pilot Moses Materu reported a technical problem in the engine
and planned to return to Arusha airport for emergency landing.
</P>
<P>
However, the plane burst into flames before falling into the
coffee farm in Burka estate, less than five kilometers from the
airport, eyewitnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The tourists had just completed tours to the well-known game
parks in Ngorongoro, Serengeti and Tarangire and were heading for
the final leg in Zanzibar for a week's holiday before returning
home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
