<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gerontological Issue in China in 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Over one-fourth of China's
population, or more than 400 million people, will reach or surpass
the age of 60 at mid-21st century, according to today's People's
Daily (overseas edition).
</P>
<P>
China has to face aging challenges in the coming century, said
demographers. Who will take care of the aged people is a grave and
urgent challenge to China in the coming century, the country's
leading newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Among China's present 120 million old people, 80 million live
in rural China. Unlike some of the elderly people in urban areas
who enjoy pension insurance, the aged rural people can only rely
on their children for the rest of their life, it said.
</P>
<P>
China has had a sharp drop in fertility since it started the
"one-child per couple" policy in 1980, and specialists predict
that China will become an aging society at the end of this
century, it noted.
</P>
<P>
The number of people above 60 will increase to 130 million by
then, 10 percent of the population, and then increase to 280
million in 2025, and to about 400 million in 2050, accounting for
more than a quarter of the country's population, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The traditional way in which the family takes care of the
elderly, however, has been weakened. One young or middler-aged
couple has to take care of four elderly and one child, meaning
resources that can provide care for the elderly are decreasing,
the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
China needs to improve its social security system while
developing its economy in the next two decades to meet the aging
challenge of the next century, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The aging population in China now accounts for 9.7 percent of
the total and is increasing by an annual average rate of 3.2
percent. "China will soon enter a gerontological society," the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary for the country to provide adequate economic
support for aged people both in the cities and the countryside
with a pension insurance system that has the widest coverage, the
paper stressed.
</P>
<P>
Demographers suggest that elderly people, on the one hand,
should have the awareness of taking care of themselves or taking
care of each other and, on the other side, the government should
establish a system that the elderly are to be taken good care of,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, the first city that has one tenth of its population
above the age of 60, has worked out insurance measures for both
workers and farmers. More than 60 percent of all rural aged people
in the city have bought pension insurance, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
