<HEADLINE> Rescuers Recover Items at Philippine Plane Crash Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Rescuers Wednesday recovered
some debris of the ill-fated Cebu Pacific DC-9 passenger plane
after they reached the crash site in the Mt. Sumagaya, Mindanao,
official military reports said.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Philippine Army headquarters at Camp
Evangelista in the Southern city of Cagayan de Oro said rescuers
retrieved passengers' calling cards, plane curtains and flags,
which were all scattered near the summit of Mt. Sumagaya.
</P>
<P>
A team of army rangers was expected to reach the exact crash
site at about 14:00 (local time). It was not known yet if the
rescuers had recovered any bodies or body parts of the victims,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Philippine national Police Chief Santiago Alino
appealed to members of the New People's Army, the armed wing of
the rebel National Democratic Front who are hiding in the mountain
area, not to attack government troops joining the search and
rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
Alino's plea came following reports that the rebel troops
opened fire at army rangers who passed by near their mountain
lair.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would welcome it if the rebels offered
to help in the ongoing search and rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
No survivors had been found at the crash site of the plane
carrying 104 people, including five crew members, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The passenger plane went missing Monday on a flight from the
capital Manila to Cagayan de Oro City, Mindanao in the Southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
While air search operations were hampered Wednesday morning due
to poor visibility in the mountain area, ground rescuer teams
continued their march toward the crash site of the plane.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine air force Tuesday spotted the wreckage site of
the Cebu Pacific plane on the northeast slope below the peak of
Mt. Sumagaya at an elevation of about 6,700 feet (2,040 meters)
above sea level.
</P>
<P>
There were conflicting reports about casualties in the air
disaster Tuesday. In the morning, the official Philippine News
Agency said members of a non-governmental organization team had
found 15 survivors and 30 bodies in Mt. Sumagaya, Claveria,
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
But the Cebu Pacific Air, the owner of the plane, said later
that reports about the survivors might not be true.
</P>
<P>
The mountainous area is on the flight route of the ill-starred
passenger plane which lost radio contact with the Lumbia airport
air tower while flying over the area.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which took off from Manila Domestic Airport at 09:30
Monday, was scheduled to land in the Lumbia airport, some 500
miles (800 km) south of Manila, at about 11:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
But the plane, which made a brief stopover in Tacloban city,
failed to arrive at the destination.
</P>
<P>
The Cebu Pacific Air, owned 49 percent by Filipino-Chinese
billionaire John Gokongwei, started operations in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The airline is one of several new airlines established after
the Philippine government deregulated the aviation industry two
and a half years ago. It has had no previous accidents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
