<HEADLINE> Mombasa-Nairobi Highway Reopens to Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's lifeline, the
Mombasa-Nairobi highway reopened to traffic on Tuesday after
Kenya Army erected a temporary bridge at River Thange, the Daily
Nation reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The line of trucks which stretched over 40 kilometers on
either side of the bridge started to move slowly, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
A.M.H. Sharawe, Permanent Secretary for Public Works of Kenya,
told the paper that the temporary bridge would be operational
until a new bridge is constructed.
</P>
<P>
Army Commander Augustine Cheruyoit instructed police to ensure
no vehicle weighing more than 60 tons is allowed through.
</P>
<P>
The highway was closed last Friday after the Thange bridge
collapsed under the force of raging flood water from Kyulu hills
following heavy rains caused by the El Nino phenomenon in the
past three months.
</P>
<P>
The highway has been closed twice in less than 20 days.
</P>
<P>
The Mombasa-Nairobi road is a vital section linking Port
Mombasa with the sections of the hinterland in Kenya, Uganda,
northern Tanzania, Rwanda, Burundi and eastern Democratic
Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
In the Coast Province, provincial Works Officer Iwiva Mpare
said, his department has started repairing all the damaged
bridges in the province.
</P>
<P>
Repairing the bridges in the whole province would cost more
than 100 million Kenyan Shillings (about 1.6 million U.S.
Dollars), he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
