<HEADLINE> Norway's Speed Skaters Practice with New Slap Skates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Norway's national champion
Njoes Grunde skated in the Nagano rink with new slap skates on
Wednesday, saying he is happy and ready for the upcoming Winter
Olympic Games slated for February 7-22.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian, who has placed several third in World Cup series in
the past, will compete in the 500m and 1,000m races in the Games.
</P>
<P>
"I am hoping for a finish in the top three here," said Grunde, who
sees the skaters from Canada and the Netherlands as his main rivals.
</P>
<P>
"The Japanese are also very good, but they are not handling the
transition to slap skates very well," Grunde said.
</P>
<P>
"I changed in Autumn 1997 while many people changed earlier than I
did -- in earlier 1997. It is not that difficult to change, but it is
difficult to get that last second which will get a time making a new
personal best.
</P>
<P>
"I haven't done it yet, but I am close and I hope to do it in the
Games."
</P>
<P>
The slap skates, an invention by a group of researchers in
biomechanics from the university of Amsterdam, were first introduced
in 1994. As the blade is only connected to the toe, the heel is
released allowing a skater to use his or her power to the full while
the blade remains on the ice for a longer period of time when a stride
is taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
