<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt, Muslim Rebels Resume Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from the Philippine
government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
resumed their initial peace talks Wednesday morning in a southern
Philippine city.
</P>
<P>
The technical committees from both sides gathered at a
university in Marawi City, capital of Lanao del Sur Province in
northern Mindanao, the local television SNN reported from the
city.
</P>
<P>
The negotiators are expected to discuss recent skirmishes
between the MILF and the government troops in Buldon Town,
Maguindanao Province, in which dozens of people on both sides were
killed and the scheduled peace talks were almost derailed.
</P>
<P>
The MILF had earlier accused the government of attacking its
camps in Maguindanao, and threatened to boycott the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Another major topic for the two-day meeting is the possibility
of and the agenda for reaching a preliminary peace agreement to
end decades of MILF separatist movement in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which had refused to be part of the peace treaty
signed in 1996 by the larger Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF)
and the government, wants a separate peace accord with Manila.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the MNLF but more radical, has
fought the government for a separate Islamic state in Mindanao
since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is currently the strongest anti-government force in
the Philippines, with an estimated 12,000 fighters.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is also seeking to open peace talks
with another Muslim rebel group, the extremist Abu Sayaaf, but the
group has shunned any contacts with the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
