<HEADLINE> Chinese Version of Sesame Street Debuts in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 4 (Xinhua) -- China and the United States
have jointly developed a Chinese version of Sesame Street, the
famous American television series for children.
</P>
<P>
Children in Shanghai, China's largest commercial center, tuned
in to the program during last week's Spring Festival, or the
Chinese Lunar New Year.
</P>
<P>
The American Children's Television Workshop and Shanghai
Television Station (SHTV) jointly sponsored production of the
TV series to provide preschool children with vivid educational
programming.
</P>
<P>
"Big Bird, one of the main puppet characters in the series,
will introduce Chinese children to wide-ranging scientific and
cultural material," according to SHTV director Sheng Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
The producers have invited some 18 experts from the fields of
education, medical science and psychology to serve as advisors.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen versions of Sesame Street, which first aired in
1969, reach an estimated 130 million children in 140 countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
