<HEADLINE> Kaunda's Son Suspected of Hiding Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The son of former Zambian
President Kenneth Kaunda was suspected of hiding arms in homes
of the opposition United National Independence Party (UNIP)
led by Kaunda, The Post reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
UNIP cadre Johannes Banda told the local newspaper on Tuesday
that a team of 10 policemen led by Detective Inspector Siafwa
raided his home and those of his two sons in Lusaka last week
searching for arms believed to have been hidden there by Kaunda's
son Major Wezi Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
"I was woken up later in the night around 22:00 hours only to
find a group of armed policemen who demanded to search my house.
They told me that they wanted to search for guns which Major
Kaunda had left in the afternoon," Banda said.
</P>
<P>
Finding nothing in Banda's house, they went to search the home
of his son, where they also didn't find anything, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"The group then searched my other son's home where they also
failed to find any guns," Banda added.
</P>
<P>
Former President Kaunda was arrested on December 25 last year
in alleged connection with the October 28 foiled coup and shifted
to house arrest six days after the arrest. 
</P>
