<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Ban on Downhill Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nagano District Court has
rejected a suit filed by an environmental group to ban the organizers
of the Nagano Olympic Winter Games to use the Alpine skiing men's
downhill course, court offcials said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The environmental group, joined by critics of the Nagano Games,
asked the court in December to ban the use of the starting area of the
course on the Happo-one slope in Habuba, saying the use violates the
law on the protection of national parks.
</P>
<P>
The courst ruled that the plaintiffs have no legal interest to ask
for an injunction while the plaintiffs said that would appeal to the
Tokyo High Court.
</P>
<P>
The men's downhill course has been a controversial topic between
the organizers and the International Ski Federation (FIS). FIS said
the original course was not worthy of Olympians and Nagano Organizing
Committee (NAOC), citing environmental concerns, repeatedly refused
FIS's request to raise it.
</P>
<P>
After five years of debate, a compromise solution was reached
between the two parties early in December last year. Under the
compromise, the start was raised from 1,680m to 1,765m above sea level
and the course will cut into the park at two places.
</P>
<P>
After solving the problem of the downhill course, NAOC
director-general Makoto Kobayashi said: "As an organising committee,
we have to balance the needs of the athletes with the protection of
the environment."
</P>
<P>
The NAOC has been making efforts to make the games environmental
friendly. They have already relocated venue sites because of nesting
birds, planted thousands of trees and even designed a paper plate
using waste apple pulp. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
