<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China and EU Witness Increased Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Statistics released by China's
General Administration of Customs show that China and the European
Union (EU) trade volume totalled 43 billion US dollars in 1997, up
8.3 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
Said figure accounted for 13.2 percent of the nation's total
foreign trade volume during the year.
</P>
<P>
China's export volume to the EU hit 23.81 billion US dollars,
up 20.1 percent on the previous year, with the import volume
rising by 3.4 percent to 19.19 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
China recorded in 1997 a trade surplus of 4.62 billion US
dollars with the EU, a region which had accounted for the major
portion of the nation's trade deficit since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Last year's trade surplus resulted from a decline in China's
imports from the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU is an important source of machinery and electronics
products, with said products accounting for more than 70 percent
of China's imports from the region.
</P>
<P>
China's demand for imported machinery and electronics products
has dropped along with continuing improvements in the domestic
production level.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the vast majority of former preferential policies
for products imported by foreign investors expired during 1997, a
fact which led to significant reductions in related imports.
</P>
<P>
The reduced demand of such products also contributed the
to decline in imports from the EU.
</P>
<P>
The processing trade sector plays a crucial role in China's
exports to the EU. The sector exported products valued at 12.32
billion US dollars to the EU during 1997, up 24.6 percent on the
previous year's figure, with the net increase in exports standing
at 2.43 billion US dollars. The figure accounted for 61 percent of
the nation's total net increase in exports to the EU.
</P>
<P>
The export value for common trade items reached 11.24 billion
US dollars, up 15.7 percent on 1996, with the the net increase
standing at 1.53 billion US dollars. The latter figure accounted
for 38.4 percent of the nation's total net increase in exports to
the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
