<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Tea Export Earnings Jump by 57 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's tea export earnings
jumped by 57 percent in the first half of the current 1997-98
fiscal year compared with that of the same period of the previous
fiscal year, an official source said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the July-December period, the country earned 1.308
billion taka (28.43 million US dollars) by exporting 16.90 million
kilograms of tea while the earnings in the corresponding period of
the last fiscal year totaled 844 million taka (18.35 million
dollars) against the export of 17.12 million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The source attributed the growth to the steep rise in tea
prices fueled by shortfall in global tea production last year.
</P>
<P>
The average price recorded in the period was 77.38 taka (1.72
dollars) per kilogram up from 49.27 taka (1.07 dollars) in the
same period of the last fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
However, the source pointed out that the country's tea output
dropped by two million kilograms in 1997 compared with the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh produced 51.5 million kilograms of tea at 156 tea
gardens in 1997, as against 53.5 million kilograms in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
