<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Urbanizes Rural And Pastoral Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The rural and pastoral parts of
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region have been increasingly
urbanized in the past several years, according to a recent study
by agriculture departments there.
</P>
<P>
The region has 191 new towns in its rural and pastoral areas,
accounting for 13.1 percent of the total. They have an average
population of 6,294, and an average non-farming population of
3,484, making up 55.4 percent of the total population, the study
reports.
</P>
<P>
These towns have 5,299 enterprises employing 163,000 workers,
many of which are privately or collectively owned, and mostly
engaged in food processing, wholesale and retail sales,
industrial construction and transport.
</P>
<P>
Many of their employees were former farmers or herdsmen, the
study says.
</P>
<P>
There are 242 markets in these towns, including 199
multi-purpose markets and 43 specialized markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
