<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Individual Income Tax Increasing in Central Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Wuhan, capital of China's Hubei
Province, collected 200 million yuan in individual income tax in
1997, a 33 percent increase from the previous year, the local tax
bureau announced here recently.
</P>
<P>
This was proceeded by moderate economic growth for the past
five years, rapid development in the iron and steel, automobile,
mechanical, electronics, and high-tech industries, and an increase
in the number of foreign-funded firms in the city, a tax bureau
official said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 630,000 people who paid taxes, 37 percent worked for
foreign-funded enterprises or the local iron and steel company,
academy of sciences, telecommunication departments, or chemical
works.
</P>
<P>
The 11,000 owners of private firms provided another 20 percent
of last year's tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the increased tax revenues was the increased
consciousness among ordinary people of the need to pay
taxes. There was a 10 percent rate of tax evasion last year, the
official said, but that is considered somewhat small. 
</P>
</TEXT>
