<HEADLINE> Comoros Secessionists Free 18 Government Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 4 (Xinhua)-- Secessionists on the Comoro
Island of Anjouan on Tuesday released 18 government soldiers,
the last held since the failed attempt in September to quash
the rebellion.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers were released under an agreement between the
secessionists and President Mohamed Taki's government brokered
last week by the Organisation of African Unity (OAU), said a
report reaching here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The release of these soldiers is a gesture of goodwill
towards the international community and the families of these
prisoners," said Foundi Abdallah Ibrahim, the leader of Anjouan's
unrecognized government.
</P>
<P>
Anjouan secessionists captured more than 100 government
soldiers during the failed attempt to quash the rebellion and
around 60 others died in the three days of fighting.
</P>
<P>
Secessionists on Anjouan and Moheli islands met the government
on Moheli last week to implement an OAU agreement signed in the
Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa in December.
</P>
<P>
The head of the OAU's liaison bureau on the Comoros Mamoudou
Kane praised the releases as a step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
Anjouan voted in a referendum last October to secede from the
Comoro islands on the grounds that federation has brought little
but poverty and a succession of coups since independence from
France in 1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
