<HEADLINE> China Making Progress in Developing Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- In today's People's Daily
China's State Education Commission reports that, during the Eighth
Five-year Plan (1991-1995) and the first two years of the Ninth
Five-year Plan (1996-2000), the country spent 1.6 billion yuan on
equipment in its normal universities and schools.
</P>
<P>
It also got 100 million US dollars in World Bank loans and 9
million US dollars from UN organizations for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, in 1996, there were 232 normal
universities and 893 secondary normal schools in China, with
603,000 and 880,000 students, respectively.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, the country also had 240 teacher training institutes
with 205,000 students, and 2,088 schools for advanced study, with
530,000 students.
</P>
<P>
In the teacher's colleges, over 30 percent of the teachers had
senior titles in 1996, up from 22 percent in 1992, and the number
for secondary normal schools rose from 9.7 percent to 13.1 percent
in the same period.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, during the 1992-1996 period, there were
2.123 million graduates of normal universities and secondary
schools and over 1.5 million middle and primary school teachers
attending various training courses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
