<HEADLINE> Vietnam Rejects U.S. Human Rights Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministry spokesman of
Vietnam Wednesday rejected the U.S. State Department report on
human rights, saying Washington has no right whatsoever to impose
its opinion on other countries.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said, by making groundless allegations on human
rights conditions in Vietnam, the U.S. has violated the basic
rules governing the international relations.
</P>
<P>
He added, the U.S. is in no position to make arbitration on
human rights in other nations.
</P>
<P>
At a time when the U.S.-Vietnamese relations are improving, it
is inappropriate for the U.S. to issue such a report, which not
only distorts facts, but also harms the development of bilateral
relations, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Nhan Dan, leading newspaper in the country, also carried a
commentary Wednesday, criticizing the U.S. for its attacks on
other countries on human rights conditions while keeping total
silence on its own gross breach of the matter.
</P>
<P>
In a report released last Friday, the U.S. State Department
slammed Vietnam's record of human rights. 
