<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> This May Be a Hard Year for Officials Guarding China's Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese officials expect to be
very busy in 1998 confronting smuggling, illegal excavations, and
the theft of relics.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Ministry of Culture said today that, since 1993,
Chinese police have investigated 4,600 crimes involving relics and
confiscated 50,000 stolen items, but many other precious items
have eluded them.
</P>
<P>
Many local officials still ignore the relics protection work
and pay attention only to the economy. As a result, nearly 1,000
relics were stolen in China last year, ministry sources say.
</P>
<P>
Chinese authorities are planning a new crackdown on these
crimes this year and will increase controls over auctioneering and
the second-hand market, sources say, and a national data base will
be built for information on relics.
</P>
<P>
This work will be especially difficult in the Three Gorges area
on the Yangtze River and the Xiaolangdi reservoir area on the
Yellow River, both of which are considered cradles of Chinese
civilization and which were dammed last year for hydro-electric
power projects.
</P>
<P>
Relics people will have to excavate and remove important sites
near the two rivers to avoid damage when the areas are
inundated. Sources say that they lack personnel and funding and
are caught in a race against time.
</P>
<P>
They will also be busy with a series of exhibitions in a year
that is the 20th anniversary of the reforms and opening up, and
the centenary of the births of several revolutionary leaders,
including Premier Zhou Enlai. Also in the works is the 50th
anniversary of the founding of New China in 1999.
</P>
<P>
There will be other items of political importance, including
the renovation of some historical sites in Yan'an, where Mao
Zedong had his headquarters in the 1940s, and Humen, where the
Opium War began in 1840. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Real Estate Sector Expects Moderate Growth By Xinhua Writer Li Jianmin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 4 (Xinhua) -- China will provide loans
totaling 100 billion yuan during 1998 to boost housing purchases
and launch vigorous housing reform which is expected to inject
vigor into the country's real estate sector.
</P>
<P>
Construction Minister Hou Jie told Xinhua today that the
housing sector has promoted national economic development and has
emerged as a major focus of consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide apartment sales to private citizens topped 42.1
billion yuan January-October 1997, up 41.8 percent on the previous
year's period.
</P>
<P>
China constructed 300 million sq.m. of urban housing, and an
additional 650 million sq.m. in rural areas during 1997, with the
total representing the most extensive housing construction over
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
Hou said China will maintain rational and stable growth in real
estate development and investment during 1998. Real estate markets
across the nation are expected to witness further growth along
with increased sales of commodity housing. Priority will be placed
on the construction of affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the improved macroeconomic environment
has created better conditions for real estate development
during 1998.
</P>
<P>
The government has placed high priority on solving housing
problems, an area considered to be a major factor in improving the
living standards of Chinese citizens. China has adopted a series
of favorable policies for developing the housing sector as a major
economic pillar.
</P>
<P>
Average individual spending on consumper items has grown from
around 10,000 yuan in the 1980s to tens of thousands of yuan
today, with housing emerging as a major expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that efforts to deepen and promote housing
reform by selling houses to Chinese citizens rather than
allocating housing as a material benefit will play decisive roles
in developing real estate markets.
</P>
<P>
An ever increasing number of Chinese citizens are purchasing
private housing, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks have introduced mortgage loan services as part
of an effort to stimulate housing purchases. In addition, a
nationwide fund-raising system provides assistance to individuals
interested in purchasing private housing.
</P>
<P>
Hou projected that real estate markets in large cities and
in both coastal and developed areas will be this year's top
performers, with real estate markets in small- to medium-sized
cities also exhibiting greater activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
