<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Westendorp Calls for Multi-ethnic Sarajevo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, February 3 (Xinhua) -- The high representative of the
peace implementation council of Bosnia, Carlos Westendorp,
Tuesday urged the Bosnian authorities to turn Sarajevo back into a
multi-ethnic city.
</P>
<P>
He linked future aid to progress on the return to the city of
Serbs and Croats.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at an international conference on returning refugee to
Moslem-dominated Sarajevo, Westendorp said Bosnian and Sarajevo
city leaders must enable the return of at least 20,000 pre-war,
minority residents in 1998. Otherwise the international community
would reduce financial aid to the country.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp appealed for the immediate and consistent
implementation of the amnesty law, which demands that refugees are
guaranteed not to have to serve in the army for at least five
years.
</P>
<P>
Conditions have to be created for returnee children to enjoy
full equality in Sarajevo schools, Westendorp said.
</P>
<P>
Sarajevo has to be an example of restoration of a multi-ethnic
society, the high representative added.
</P>
<P>
Robert Gelbard, special United States envoy to the former
Yugoslavia, was even more specific. He said authorities in
Sarajevo and the Muslim-Croat Federation had two weeks to change
the existing laws on property.
</P>
<P>
A failure to respect this deadline could lead to the instant
stoppage of U.S. aid for the reconstruction of Sarajevo Canton,
Gelbard added.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian tripartite presidency chairman, Alija Izetbegovic, said
he personally, and the Bosniak side, supported the initiative in
declaring Sarajevo an open city. But he dismissed criticism that
the multi-ethnic structure of Sarajevo had been dramatically
changed.
</P>
<P>
According to Izetbegovic, there are 308,000 Muslims and 45,600
Croats, Serbs and members of other nationalities living in
Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
At least one-third of the canton and city administration
employees are non-Bosnians, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian leader presented five conditions for a speedier
return of refugees to Sarajevo.--
</P>
<P>
Nobody at present living in other people's apartments should be
evicted and all those who wanted to return would not be able to
rent or sell their apartments for at least five years. A law on
returning should be adopted by the whole of Bosnia-Herzegovina;
Sarajevo as the capital should become the real seat of all joint
institutions of authority and the return conditions would be
common to all groups.
</P>
<P>
"Banja Luka must follow the example of Sarajevo immediately,"
Izetbegovic demanded. Otherwise he would not accept any of the
conclusions of the Sarajevo conference.
</P>
<P>
Bosnian Presidency Croat member Kresimir Zubak warned however
that the setting of new conditions was a new attempt to prevent
the return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
Zubak demanded the rescinding of illegal decisions which took
away tenancy rights from people who left Sarejevo during the war
and, for all, the unobstructed use of one's own property.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that the proclamation of a district in the area of
Sarajevo be reconsidered. This would secure equality for all
Sarajevco residents, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the conference, a declaration was passed which
obliges Bosnian authorities to amend the laws that made it
impossible for Sarajevo refugees to return to the apartments flats
where they lived before the war.
</P>
<P>
"If they (the authorities) do not comply they will be
penalized," the declaration threatened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
