<HEADLINE> Bad Weather Hampers Rescue Efforts in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Bad Weather and unfavorable
environment have hindered the search and rescue efforts Wednesday
at the crash site of the ill-fated Cebu Pacific aircraft on the
mountain slopes of Mt. Sumagaya, in Misamis Oriental, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The official Philippine News Agency quoted Henry Cinco,
spokesman of the government army, as saying that elements of the
special forces of the Philippine Air Force's emergency rescue team
are now heading toward the crash site.
</P>
<P>
He said the special forces jumped off Tuesday afternoon toward
the actual crash site but was still six hours away from the area
as of 11 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Cinco said the rescue team members are moving cautiously due to
slippery boulders and densely thick foliage inhabited by leeches
and dangerous insects.
</P>
<P>
He said the actual site was spotted 150 meters below the summit
of Mt. Sumagaya.
</P>
<P>
Cinco said it was impossible to drop provisions and other
support elements in the area due to steep slopes and deep gullies.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Cinco said, the weather in the area is unpredictable,
prompting some volunteers accompanying the airbone's special
forces to return to base in the morning.
</P>
<P>
He said the search and rescue teams have been regularly
informing the command center of "Task Force Pacific", a combined
search and rescue operations of the Philippines Air Force,
Philippine Army and the management of Cebu Pacific Air stationed
at the Cagayan de Oro airport, of their location and movements
every two hours.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, local television reports said that some rescuers have
already reached the crash site and found several items of the
plane wreckage and personal belongings of 104 people aboard the
plane, which crashed Monday on its way from Manila to Cagayan de
Oro.
</P>
<P>
But the reports have not been officially confirmed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
