<HEADLINE> Eastern China Has More Favorable Policies For Private Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, February 4 (Xinhua) -- China's Zhejiang Province,
which has the second largest group of private firms in the
country, has worked out preferential policies for its private
sector, according to Vice-Governor Lu Songting.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the new policies is to create a better
environment for private businesses in the areas of taxation,
loans, land and power supplies as well as exports to help them compete with
other companies on an equal footing, Lu says, adding that local
private companies are encouraged to use more advanced technology
and modern management.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, the province had 90,000 private
enterprises, with 47 billion yuan (5.6 billion U.S. dollars) in
registered capital, second in the country after Guangdong Province, which
borders Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang also has 1.5 million individually-owned industrial and
commercial businesses, with 21.9 billion yuan in registered
capital, more than the country's average.
</P>
<P>
The growing private sector has become a major employer of
people laid off by state-owned factories and has played a big role
in local poverty-elimination efforts. So far, 839 of them have
formed a partnership with 111 impoverished villages and counties
to help them out. Some 62,000 workers who were laid off by
state-owned enterprises have found new jobs in private
business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
