<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nearly 4,000 Seek Asylum in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 3 (Xinhua) - The number of asylum seekers that
have entered Bulgaria has been estimated to be from 2,000 to 4,000.
</P>
<P>
The figure was cited at a two-day workshop on Police and
Refugee Problems. The workshop opened in Sandanski, southwestern
Bulgaria, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 aliens have been formally granted refugee status by
the Bulgarian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Asylum seekers are mainly from countries strickened by armed
conflicts. As a rule, they do not carry identity papers.
</P>
<P>
There are also many persons seeking asylum who may be
associated with criminal groups that seek refugee status in a bid
to gain legal residence in Bulgaria. Though there have been few
such cases so far, past experience from other countries suggests
that an increase is possible.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria is the only country in Europe which does not yet have
a refugee law, said Hristo Ivanov of the Higher Institute for
Officer Training and Scientific Research under the Ministry of the
Interior.
</P>
<P>
A bill has been finalized and parliament is expected to pass it
before the end of this year. One of the top priorities is to
harmonize Bulgarian human rights legislation with European law.
</P>
<P>
In 1992 Bulgaria signed the convention relating to the status
of refugees and is obliged to provide decent living conditions for
people considered refugees. Officials however claim the country
cannot afford the costs, since it too is experiencing a financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Office of the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees provides
financial assistance in two ways: through targeted grants to the
state itself and through aid to non-governmental organizations
implementing the refugee protection program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Proposes Guarantee Plan to Indonesian Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Singapore has proposed a
multilateral guarantee plan to help Indonesia "unlock" part of its
international financial crisis, local newspapers reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, according to the reports, involves several
countries that would guarantee payment for Indonesian imports and
was put forward by Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong who met with
Indonesian President Soeharto in Jakarta on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Goh said that the proposal, which he discussed with Soeharto
during a meeting that lasted 95 minutes Tuesday evening, could, if
accepted, provide the Indonesian central bank with up to 20
billion US dollars in foreign guarantee.
</P>
<P>
"Letters of Credit (LCs) issued by Indonesian banks are not
being accepted by foreign banks. We have to unlock this. If we do
not unlock this, LCs are not accepted, imports cannot go in," the
Singapore leader said.
</P>
<P>
"If imports are stuck, then of course, the export industries do
not have the components for goods to be manufactured for export.
We have to find a way for LCs to be accepted," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta announced last week that it would guarantee all
deposits and debts of Indonesian banks. But many foreign banks
were still not accepting their letters of credit. Analysts were
quoted as saying that even some of the big banks had been using
customer deposits to cover other obligations and delaying payment
to LC holders.
</P>
<P>
Goh reportedly said that a multilateral forum was "more
flexible". It would take a little more time to implement compared
to a bilateral agreement. But if only eight countries joined the
consortium and put up one billion US dollars each, there would be
eight billion US dollars for Indonesian imports "straight away".
</P>
<P>
"Of course, we hope that we can get something like 20 billion
US dollars," he said. And the Indonesian authorities, with central
bank reserves currently at around 20 billion US dollars, have long
said that the amount would be good for five months' worth of
imports.
</P>
<P>
Goh said that Singapore would put up a paper elaborating on the
proposal to President Soeharto soon, and wait for his decision.
"Once the president approves, we can launch," he added.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto welcomed the multilateral scheme, the reports said. He
said Australia had already agreed to guarantee Indonesian imports
of certain commodities, as had the United States.
</P>
<P>
"In reality, we have enough foreign exchange reserves to pay
for the LCs, but because there is a lack of confidence, we are
forced to finally seek help from other countries to take part in
guaranteeing the LCs," he said.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, he said, would allow Indonesia to import again and
boost its exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Rescuers Reach Plane Crash Site, Items Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Rescuers reached the wreckage
site of a Cebu Pacific passenger plane in a mountain area in
Mindanao Wednesday morning, and have reportedly found several
items of the plane wreckage and personal belongings of passengers.
</P>
<P>
According to local television reports, the items found in the
crash site in Mt. Sumagaya, Misamis Oriental, Mindanao, have been
sent to the Cebu Pacific Air for verification.
</P>
<P>
So far, no survivors have been found at the crash site of the
plane carrying 104 people, including five crew members, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The passenger plane went missing Monday on a flight from the
Philippine capital of Manila to Cagayan de Oro City, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
While air search operations were hampered Wednesday morning due
to visibility in the mountain area, ground rescuers continued
their march toward the crash site of the plane.
</P>
<P>
But government rescue teams composed of government soldiers and
the national police have reportedly clashed with members of the
rebel New People's Army.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine air force Tuesday spotted the wreckage site of
the Cebu Pacific plane on the northeast slope below the peak of
Mt. Sumagaya at an elevation of about 6,700 feet (2,043.5 meters)
above sea level.
</P>
<P>
There were conflicting reports about casualties in the air
disaster Tuesday. In the morning, the official Philippine News
Agency said that members of a non-government organization team
have found 15 survivors and 30 dead bodies in Mt. Sumagaya,
Claveria, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
But the Cebu Pacific Air, the owner of the plane, said later
that reports about the survivors might not be true.
</P>
<P>
The mountainous area is on the flight route of the ill-fated
passenger plane which lost radio contact with the Lumbia airport
air tower while flying over the area before approaching the
airport.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which took off from the Manila Domestic Airport at
09:30 a.m. Monday, was scheduled to land in the Lumbia airport,
some 500 miles south of Manila, at about 11:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
But the plane, which made a brief stopover in Tacloban city,
failed to arrive at the destination.
</P>
<P>
The Cebu Pacific Air, owned 49 percent by Filipino-Chinese
billionaire John Gokongwei, started operations in March 1996.
</P>
<P>
The airline is one of several new airlines established after
the Philippine government deregulated the aviation industry two
and a half years ago. It has had no previous accidents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
