<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Parliament Approves NATO Observations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 3 (Xinhua) - The Bulgarian Parliamentary
Committee on Foreign Policy adopted, with an overwhelming
majority, observations on the implementation of the program for
Bulgaria's accession to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO).
</P>
<P>
The document was approved by a vote of 15 to 3, with two
abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Restructuring of the Bulgarian army, preparing the country for
its integration into the alliance and international activities
that would result in Bulgaria being invited to join NATO are the
three goals stated in the observations, said Committee Chairman
Assen Agov, MP of the Union of Democratic Forces (UDF).
</P>
<P>
The paper provides an analysis and an estimate of the
government's performance on the integration process.
</P>
<P>
Though the paper is only a working document which is not
politically binding, it, however, reflects the will of the
majority of Bulgarians for NATO membership, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
Agov said it was extremely important to get the observations
approved before President Petar Stoyanov left for the United
States. In view of the coming high-level talks there, parliament's
approval would strengthen the president's position in defending
Bulgaria's interests.
</P>
<P>
However, the Democratic Left, the opposition party, sounded
different notes on the issue. It said Bulgaria's NATO membership
should be decided by a referendum, following a public debate.
</P>
<P>
The national debate should answer questions concerning the
current direction of NATO's development, prospects of the
deployment of military bases and nuclear weapons on Bulgarian
territory and possible participation of Bulgarian armed forces in
NATO military operations in conflict zones. It should look at the
future of the Bulgarian military-industrial complex and the cost
of bringing the Bulgarian army in line with NATO standards.
</P>
<P>
Peter Bashikarov, deputy chairman of the committee, said on
national radio: "Within the framework of cooperation with the
Euro-Atlantic structures we support Partnership for Peace.
</P>
<P>
"We are not against NATO or against expanding contacts with
this organization," he said, expressing the Left's opinion.
"However, accession to NATO is something forced upon us, which we
have never accepted." 
</P>
</TEXT>
