<HEADLINE> Iraqi Envoy Denies Capacity of Attcking Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 3 (Xinhua)-- Iraq' representative to
the United Nations Nizar Hamdoon Tuesday reiterated that his
country did not have the missiles or any other weapons capable of
hitting Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamdoon made the remarks while answering a question from a
listener in Israel during an interview with U.S. Cable News
Network (CNN). The listener was deeply concerned about possible
attacks on Israel by Iraq in retaliation against U.S. strikes.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq has not made such announcements," Hamdoon said, adding
that his country "has no capacity of any long-range missiles or
any other biological or chemical weapons."
</P>
<P>
"All these have been destroyed," the representative said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's concerns came after an interview by the New York Times
late last month with a head of the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSOM). The UNSCOM head alleged that Iraq still has
capacity of missiles hitting Israel and elsewhere in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, he had no evidence to prove the allegations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
