<HEADLINE> Poland, Germany to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, February 2 (Xinhua) -- Polish Prime Minister Jerzy
Buzek left here for Bonn on Tuesday for a two-day work visit to
Germany.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Buzek will meet his German counterpart
Chancellor Helmut Kohl and other German political and business
figures. Invited by the German Society for Foreign Policy and the
Bonn University, Buzek will give a speech on the prospects for
Poland in an integrated Europe.
</P>
<P>
The trip is reportedly another effort by the Polish government
to strengthen bilateral ties with Germany, a NATO member, before
it starts formal accession talks with NATO member states.
</P>
<P>
Poland values its ties with Germany and takes Germany as its
biggest and most strategic partner in foreign policy. The two
countries have exchanged frequent political contacts at various
levels since they signed border and cooperative agreements, and
established friendly ties and cooperation in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The two countries held their first governmental consultative
meeting last July, which makes Poland the first country Germany
has had such contacts with besides EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Germany is also Poland's major trading partner. According to
the Polish Press Agency. Bilateral trading volume reached 31.5
billion German marks last year. Poland is Germany's biggest
trading partner among Central-Eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
Germany is ranked as Poland's second largest investor, with
investment from Germany reaching 4 billion German marks by the end
of 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
