<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government Denies Wider Rich-Poor Gap in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government
Wednesday denied claims of the Catholic Bishops Conference that
the "rich became richer and the poor poorer" in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here, Socio-economic Planning
Secretary Cielito Habito said that the claims of the conference
recently are not supported by objective data and indicators taken
by local and external analysts.
</P>
<P>
"While the government accepts that much work remains to be done
in fighting poverty, to say that the income disparities between
rich and poor have widened is unfair," Habito said.
</P>
<P>
Income shares of the rich Filipinos have also been
redistributed towards the middle and lower income groups, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that shares of total income of families belonging to
the top 20 percent declined from 53.9 percent in 1991 to 51
percent in 1994 while those in the lower income group improved
their shares from 8.5 to 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Habito said that the human development index of the United
Nations Development Program indicating life expectancy, education
and gross domestic product per capita, shows an improvement in the
Philippines from 0.621 in 1992 to 0.672 in 1994, the latest
available measure for the index.
</P>
<P>
The improvement took place even at the time when the economic
growth was still below 5 percent and unemployment rate was still
higher at 9-10 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
"More recent years have in fact seen further improvement in the
indictors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Habito said that improved provision of basic social services
such as school rooms and health services should also be seen as
part of the overall package of poverty alleviation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, Japan Set Up Economic Cooperation Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar and Japan have reached
an agreement on establishment of an economic cooperation committee
to enhance the economic cooperation of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached here Tuesday between the Myanmar
Chamber of Commerce and Industry and the Japanese Chamber of
Commerce and Industry, the official New Light of Myanmar newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The setting up of the economic cooperation committee between
the two chambers came more than seven months after a workshop on
Myanmar-Japan economic cooperation was held here last June.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Japan's investment in Myanmar
amounted to 202.63 million U.S. dollars in 16 permitted projects,
ranking the ninth out of a total foreign investment of 6.6 billion
dollars from 23 countries or regions by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Japan, a major donor to Myanmar in the past, has extended to
the country for 18 times grant-in-aid for debt relief. The last
aid provided in June 1997 was 2 billion yen (16 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japan has also extended to Myanmar a total grant aid
of 447,045 U.S. dollars since last November to help
implementation of agricultural and health projects in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
