<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Restructure Two More banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is set to
take drastic action against two more local commercial banks which
failed to increase their capitals, the local press reported on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand is expected to announce rehabilitation
plans soon for the First Bangkok City Bank (FBCB) and Siam City
Bank (SCIB) due to their failure to recapitalize as well as their
delay in bringing in foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank's move against the two medium-sized banks
will be the second round clean-up of the country's banking system.
</P>
<P>
The Thai central bank last month took over Bangkok Metropolitan
Bank whose share par value slumped to 0.01 Baht from 10 Baht.
</P>
<P>
However, what action the banking regulators will take against
FBCB and SCIB remains uncertain and some foreign banks still have
not given a definite answer on their acquisition plans for the two
Thai banks.
</P>
<P>
FBCB and SCIB reportedly have borrowed massive short-term money
from the central bank's Financial Institution Development Fund
(FIDF) to ease their liquidity crises.
</P>
<P>
FBCB, in which liquor tycoon Charoen Sirivadhanaphakdi has a 35
percent stake, is believed to have borrowed 100 billion Baht
(about 2 billion U.S. Dollars) from the FIDF alone.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the two banks are likely to face massive
capital writedowns which will significantly bring down their
shareholders' equity.
</P>
<P>
The two banks reportedly are in talks with foreign banks for
recapitalization and Thai Central Bank Governor Chaiyawat
Wibulswasdi said that the authorities will consider carefully
rehabilitation plans for the banks before making further
announcements on their future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
