<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Storm, Rains Hit U.S. West Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 3 (Xinhua) -- El Nino-charged storms and
drenching rains hit the West Coast of the United States Tuesday
and Wednesday, uprooting trees, sweeping away motorhomes, breaking
windows and closing down highways in northern and southern
California.
</P>
<P>
The storm caused extensive damage and wreaked widespread havoc,
By Monday night, the storm was hitting the San Francisco Bay Area
in full force, causing power outages and shutting down roads.
</P>
<P>
Stanford University canceled classes Tuesday because of
flooding throughout the campus.
</P>
<P>
An inch-an-hour fell in many areas of Southern California
Monday. Residents were told to stay home and watch the news on
TV. Drenching rains, hail, lightning and hurricane-force winds
blasted out windows and topped trees while 18-feet waves chewed at
sand-berm protecting beach homes.
</P>
<P>
Pounding rains flooded highways, intersections and airport
runways, forcing two airlines to cancel flights at San Barbara
Airport. Storm winds raked one region, knocking out power to tens
of thousands of homes.
</P>
<P>
The last disastrous El Nino event, which took place in the
U.S. West Coast in 1982-83, brought about 250 million U.S. dollars
of damage. Scientists view this year's El Nino as an unprecedented
opportunity to study one of nature's least-understood
phenomena. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Trade Deficit Down in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lima, February 3 (Xinhua) ----Peru's trade deficit in 1997 was
down 16.3 percent to 1.6 billion U.S. dollars, with imports of 8.3
billion dollars and exports of 6.7 billion dollars, the National
Superintendent of Customs said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The customs office attributed the decreasing deficit to the
rapid growth of exports, which registered an increase of 15.5
percent. The country's export volume also reached a historic
record high.
</P>
<P>
The growth is supported primarily by traditional mining and
fishing exports, which increased 58 and 23 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The non-traditional exports in 1997 reached 2.04 billion
dollars, up 28 percent from the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Twenty Killed in Cable Car Crash in Northern Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 3 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Marine warplane hit and cut
a cable car line in northern Italy Tuesday, causing a cable car to
crash into the hillside with all the 20 people aboard killed.
</P>
<P>
Italy's ANSA news agency reported that the accident occurred in
Cavalese City of Trento Province in northern Italy and that the
warplane landed back at its base with the crew apparently unaware
of what had happened.
</P>
<P>
The cable car was traveling from the town of Cavalese to the
top of Cermis mountain, the site of a popular local ski resort in
northern Italy, when the warplane hit and cut the cable car line
with its tail surface, ANSA said.
</P>
<P>
Italian Defense Ministry sources in Rome said that when the
plane made an emergency landing at the NATO base at Aviano, which
is about 100 kilometers east of the scene of the accident, the
pilot reported that he had simply felt a "big bump."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Marine Ea-6b electronic warfare plane, deployed at
Aviano for service with the U.N. Stabilization Force in Bosnia,
was on a scheduled training mission in the area, the Defense
Ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
The passengers and the car's operator aboard were killed when
it fell 80-100 meters. The victims include Germans, Belgians,
Poles and Italians.
</P>
<P>
Of those killed, nine were women and eleven were men. The
car's operator, identified as Marcello Vanzo, should have been
off-duty, but he had taken over someone else's shift at the last
moment, according to ANSA.
</P>
<P>
Senior Airman Monte Volk, a spokesman at the Aviano base, was
quoted as saying by the local media that the plane was on a
"low-level training mission" when the accident occured at 3:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The Ea-6b is a surveillance aircraft capable of carrying a crew
of four.
</P>
<P>
The accident drew immediate responses from political circles in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Refoundation party renewed its call to close the
Aviano base.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other lawmakers demanded an end to U.S. military
flights over inhabited areas, and punishment for the pilot.
</P>
<P>
Trento authorities opened an investigation into the cause of
the accident.
</P>
<P>
Italian Premier Romano Prodi sent his condolences.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton, in a phone call to Prodi,
expressed his condolences for the victims of the crash. Clinton
reportedly assured Prodi that both U.S. and Italian officials will
be fully involved in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also pledged to take steps so that no similar disasters
occur again, the Italian premier's office was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Aviano is the largest U.S. air base in Italy, with nearly 6,000
military and civilian personnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
