<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Castro Insists on End to Embargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, February 3, (Xinhua) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro
lashed out at the longstanding United States embargo against the
country on Monday and reiterated that Washington should end it as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"Cuba does not demand humanitarian aid from the United
States. It demands an end to the economic war against our people,
and that it respects our right to develop ourselves economically
and trade freely with all the people of the world," Castro said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark in a live television address to analyze Pope
John Paul II's first visit to Cuba on January 21-25.
</P>
<P>
John Paul II also condemned the embargo, saying it contributed
to hardship on the island.
</P>
<P>
During his four-hour speech, Castro criticized a recent
proposal by the Miami-headquartered Cuban-American National
Foundation to provide humanitarian aid to Cuba without dismantling
the more-than-40-year-old economic blockade of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that the plan was an offering intended to suffocate
Cuba's economy and to diminish the honor of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
