<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0200 GMT February 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze said Tuesday
that relations with Russia remain one of the priorities of
Georgia's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax Agency quoted Shevardnadze as saying in an annual
address to the parliament that Georgia's ultimate goal is to
establish new and equitable relations with Russia.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia's involvement in the implementation of the
Eurasian corridor global project and its investment in the
Georgian economy may bring colossal advantages to both countries.
(Georgia-Russia-Relations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- Female condoms will appear in the Tanzanian
market in the first quarter of this year, local media reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The female condoms, to be distributed by the Population
Services International (PSI), are aimed at preventing HIV and
other sexually transmitted diseases (STDs), as well as unwanted
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
"We are now working on a research to determine its
acceptability in Tanzania," Dr. Richard Frank, the president of
PSI, told reporters at the Sheraton Hotel here Monday.
(Tanzania-Female Condoms)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Culture and Information Ministry has started
to expand its press center to face the increasing influx of
foreign reporters before a possible U.S. military strike against
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Director General Uday al-Taie of the Iraqi News Agency (INA)
told reporters Tuesday that the current press center, founded
after the 1991 Gulf War, provides press services in both Arabic
(from 07:00 GMT to 21:00 GMT) and English (from 09:00 GMT to
15:00 GMT) through INA. (Iraq-Press Center)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERN, Switzerland -- China's Vice Premier Li Lanqing met here
today with Swiss Federal Councillor and Minister of Finance Kaspar
Villiger.
</P>
<P>
The two were satisfied with the two countries' relationship of
friendship and cooperation and agreed that constant exchanges of
visits at a high level had vigorously promoted the development of
mutual relations.
</P>
<P>
Li said that since the establishment of foreign relations in
1950, the relationship between China and Switzerland has been
developed in an overall smooth way. The Sino-Swiss relationship
has been closer and closer in recent years, he added.
(Switzerland-China-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUSAKA -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba here Tuesday
denied the speculations that he was shot and injured last week,
according to Zambia News Broadcasting Corporation Limited (ZNBC).
</P>
<P>
When touring in the capital, Chiluba said with a smile to
people that he is in good condition and the rumors that he was
shot is false.
</P>
<P>
Local and foreign reports said last week that the Zambian
president was assassinated and Chiluba's disappearance in the
public for several days fueled the
speculation. (Zambia-assassination)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan Tuesday
telephoned Iraq's Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz and they
discussed the growing crisis over Iraq's weapons inspection, U.N.
spokesman Eckhard Fred said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"They discussed the seriousness of the situation and the need
to get results," Eckhard told reporters at the noon briefing.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general initiated the talks and described the
conversation as `constructive.' They agreed on the need to speed
up efforts to find a negotiated solution to the problem," the
spokesman said. (UN-Annan-Aziz-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- President of Armenia Levon Ter-Petrosyan announced
his resignation at the national television Tuesday evening, the
Itar-Tass news agency reported from Yerevan, capital of Armenia.
</P>
<P>
The president's resignation came in the wake of a political
crisis in the solution of the Nagorno-Karabakh problem, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Ter-Petrosyan's resignation was preceded by a string of
resignations of officials close to the president.
(Armenia-President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada's French-speaking province of Quebec has said
it is determined to fight the high suicide rate, which is at 19
for every 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The rate is the third highest in the industrialized world,
behind only Hungary and Finland, whose suicide rates are at 34 and
27 for per 100,000 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Quebec Health Minister Jean Rochon has announced that his
government will spend over 700,000 dollars (480,000 US dollars)
over three years on prevention programs and public education.
</P>
<P>
The government has already spent close to 2.5 million dollars
on the suicide problem, said reports Tuesday.
(Canada-Quebec-Suicide)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Twenty people were killed in a cable car crash in
northern Italy Tuesday, which came after a U.S. navy warplane hit
and cut the mountain cable way hanging the cable car.
</P>
<P>
Italy's ANSA news agency reported that the accident occurred in
Cavalese City of Trento Province in northern Italy and that the
warplane landed back at its base with the crew apparently unaware
of what had happened. (Italy-Cable Car Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JENAIRO -- the Federal Police of Brazil confiscated 31.7
tons of marijuana and 4.1 of cocaine in 1997, police authorities
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The confiscation of marijuana represented an increment of 41.5
percent over the 22.4 tons in 1996 and cocaine increased 32.2
percent over the 3.1 percent of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ninty-eight percent of the destroyed marijuana was from the
Northeast of the country. The larger confiscations of cocaine came
from the Central-East region, the police said. (Brazil-Marijuana)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States would not pledge as asked for
by Olympic leaders not to mount any strike on Iraq during the
Winter Olympic games.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic leaders earlier on Tuesday expressed their concerns
that the United States might destroy a U.N.-backed "Olympic Truce"
by bombing Iraq during the February 7-22 Winter Games in Nagano,
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Juan Antonio Samaranch, the International Olympic Committee
president, said in Nagano: "The IOC hopes that the Olympic truce
will be observed during the Nagano Games." (US-Iraq-Arms
Inspections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- French president's special envoy Bertrand Dufourcq
arrived here Tuesday evening with the aim of reaching a solution
to defuse the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
The French envoy will discuss with Iraqi officials the
prospects of a solution of the current crisis between Iraq and the
United States, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported, without
giving further details.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, well-informed sources told Xinhua that Dufourcq will
also meet with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein Wednesday to deliver
a letter from French President Jacques Chirac. (Iraq-France-Envoy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli scientists at the Weizmann Institute have
developed new materials that can significantly improve the
promising cancer therapy, the Photodynamic therapy (PDT), the
institute announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the institute's spokesman's office
said the new materials were derived from chlorophyll, the green
pigment that allows plants to capture sunlight. These materials
can overcome the problems that the PDT therapy is facing in
treating bulky and solid tumors. (Israel-Cancer-New Therapy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- A Tornado warplane of German air forces Tuesday crashed
over northern Germany, which is the second such accident involving
a Tornado in two weeks, according to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The pilot and co-pilot ejected to safety before the plane went
down near the town of Lippstadt in the state of North
Rhine-Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
What caused the crash remains unknown yet. On January 20, a
navy Tornado crashed over the North Sea near the island of Borkum,
killing both of the two crewmen. (Germany-Plane Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides Tuesday
stressed that the only settlement of the Cyprus question is to
reunify the island based on the United Nations resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides' comments were in response to a statement by
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, who recently told former
Greek premier Constantinos Mitsotakis that Turkish officials have
come to the conclusion that division is the sole solution in
Cyprus. (Cyprus-Turkey-Reunification) 
</P>
