<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Continues Aid Programs for Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO de JANEIRO, February 3 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will have
channeled a total of 2.47 billion U.S. dollars into Brazil, from
June last year to the end of this year, to help the country's
reform programs in agriculture and banking supervision.
</P>
<P>
About 64.7 percent of the total, or 1.6 billion dollars, was
spent over the last six months in 1997, the bank director Gobind
Nankani said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that another 150 million dollars would be invested this
year to address projects on agricultural reforms to benefit
15,000 farm families.
</P>
<P>
Another project which the bank director mentioned was a loan of
20 million dollars to the Brazil central bank so as to help
improve its banking supervision system.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank funded resources of 500 million dollars to
Brazil in 1994. With this, Brazilian authorities succeeded in
completing the "Plan Real" designed to reduce inflation in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
