<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Urged to Spend Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 4 (Xinhua) -- The Bankers Association of the
Philippines (BAP) is appealing to the government to refrain from
spending more than it earns in order to help reduce interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal restraint would be best way for the government to lead
in bringing down the interest rates in the country, according to
BAP President Deogracias Vistan, quoted Wednesday by local daily
the Philippine Journal.
</P>
<P>
Vistan said if the government, through the Department of
Finance, will not heed the call of the private financial sector to
follow this recommendation, it is likely that interest rates will
stay high.
</P>
<P>
Banks' interest rates, especially lending rates, have been
raised considerably after the de facto devaluation of the
Philippine peso in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Vistan said that right now the interest rates continue to rise
because the Bureau of Treasury is considering the high offer of
the private financial institutions during auctions of the Treasury
Bills and Treasury Bonds.
</P>
<P>
But Vistan is optimistic that the government will be able to
cut down on its expenditures by reviewing its priorities for the
year.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) has asked the
government to generate a budget surplus of 27 billion pesos (675
million U.S. dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In response, the government has instructed all government
offices to save at least 25 percent of their annual budget this
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
