<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Registers Unusual High Temperatures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, February 3 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian cities of
Sao Paulo and Rio de Janeiro registered in January unusual high
temperatures regarded as a result of the climatic phenomenon "El
Nino," the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
January was the hottest month of the last 42 years in Brazil,
with the medium maximum temperature reaching 30.8 degrees Celsius,
slightly below that of 30.9 degrees Celsius registered in 1956
when the Brazil National Institute of Meteorology (INMETB) started
to operate.
</P>
<P>
The medium temperature in Sao Paulo in January was
approximately 27.5 degrees Celsius, but on January 23 the city
registered a temperature of 34.2 degrees Celsius, local press
reports quoted the INMETB authorities as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rio de Janeiro, the second largest city of Brazil, registered a
temperature surpassing 40 degrees Celsius in the past three days.
The city is full of tourists and the temperature reached 41.5
degrees Celsius on February 1.
</P>
<P>
Neide Oliveira, an expert with the National Meteorological
Institute, said that there are several factors that have
influenced the change of temperatures, such as "El Nino" that
caused a rain decrease.
</P>
<P>
According to the meteorologist, the high temperature will
continue in the following days on some regions of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
