<HEADLINE> U.S. Avoids Pledge not to Attack Iraq during </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States would
not pledge as asked for by Olympic leaders not to mount any
strike on Iraq during the Winter Olympic games.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic leaders earlier on Tuesday expressed their
concerns that the United States might destroy a U.N.-backed
"Olympic Truce" by bombing Iraq during the February 7-22 Winter
Games in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Juan Antonio Samaranch, the International Olympic Committee
president, said in Nagano: "The IOC hopes that the Olympic truce
will be observed during the Nagano Games."
</P>
<P>
But U.S. State Department spokesman James Foley told reporters:
"All I can tell you is that we don't have timelines or deadlines."
</P>
<P>
"We respect the call for peace connected with the Olympics.
But we are working at the same time with friends and allies to
ensure Iraq's compliance with its obligations under mandatory
U.N. Security Council resolutions," Foley said at a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the diplomatic efforts made by Russia, France
and Arab states to defuse the current standoff with Iraq over
weapons inspections, Foley said the United States had no
objections to these efforts, but he insisted that there could be
"no negotiation" over the U.N. demand for total access to any
sites suspected of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of diplomacy of any kind, no matter what kind of
envoys from what nations we're talking about, is simply to
achieve full compliance on the part of Saddam Hussein," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
