<HEADLINE> Women VIPs Call for Support for Rights of Afghan Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 3 (Xinhua) -- A panel of prominent women
today called on the international community to show its support
for Afghan women, who they say have been stripped of rights that
women around the world take for granted.
</P>
<P>
The panel of women, representing a core group of 50
internationally known women -- ministers, Nobel prize winners, as
well as politicians and intellectuals -- launched an appeal for
the women of Afghanistan Tuesday in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
The panel presented this initiative as part of a world-wide
campaign originally promoted by the European Parliament, which
includes a big variety of initiatives taken by women and human
rights organizations throughout the EU and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is aimed at mobilizing international public
opinion on March 8 of 1998, the international women's day, around
the issue of the rights denied to the women of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The appeal calls on all member governments of the United
Nations, as well as on all international organizations, to do
whatever is in their power to help restore the basic human rights
of women in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The European Community Humanitarian Office (ECHO), which is
committed to raising public awareness about the humanitarian
crisis in Afghanistan, is supporting the campaign.
</P>
<P>
The panel includes EU commissioners Emma Bonino and Anita
Gradin. 
