<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Nuclear Ban Treaty in America's Interest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Tuesday that a treaty to ban global nuclear weapons tests "is
in America's interest."
</P>
<P>
"The test ban treaty will hold other nations to the standards
we now observe. With the treaty enforced, we will gain a powerful
new tool," said Clinton, who is visiting the Los Alamos National
Laboratory in New Mexico, the birthplace of the world's first
atomic bomb.
</P>
<P>
The visit was designed to help Clinton "speak from firsthand
experience" when he proposed a comprehensive test ban treaty to
the Senate this year, White House officials said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has submitted the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty to the
Senate for ratification, and the White House expects a difficult
battle in a drive to get it passed this year as Republicans
questioned whether the country's atomic arsenal can be properly
maintained without testing them.
</P>
<P>
To answer Republican concerns about U.S. nuclear weapons,
Clinton has proposed a package of safeguards such as expanding
intelligence, monitoring and verification of other countries'
nuclear programs to go along with the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's visit to the scientific facilities was to undercore
that the United States would still be able to maintain a safe and
reliable nuclear stockpile without detonating any weapons.
</P>
<P>
He observed a nuclear test simulation performed by the
so-called "Blue Mountain" supercomputer at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory. The lab is turning its attention from traditional
stockpile management, like underground tests, to computer-run
experiments without an explosion.
</P>
<P>
Clinton proposed in his fiscal 1999 budget 517 million U.S.
dollars for the Accelerated Strategic Computering Initiative in
which the Los Alamos lab and two others in Albuquerque and
California would be able to develop faster supercomputers and
other methods for maintaining the nuclear stockpile without
testing.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we can get the treaty ratified unless we can
convince the Senate that the stockpile stewardship program works,
that we can be secure while we try to make the world safer from
nuclear development," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The treaty has been signed by 156 countries, including nuclear
powers Britain, France, China, the United States and Russia. But
it has been ratified by only 10 states.
</P>
<P>
The United States conducted its last nuclear test in 1992, but
in 1993 Clinton extended a moratorium on underground testing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: Attack on Iraq would Be Serious </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S Defense Secretary
William Cohen said on Tuesday that any strike on Iraq would be
more serious than ever mounted since the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In answering questions at the Senate Armed Services Committee,
Cohen said that once decided, the attack from the formidable U.S.
force assembled in the Gulf would be aimed at "dealing him (Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein) a severe blow" to ensure he was unable
to "pose any kind of a threat to his neighbors."
</P>
<P>
He said any U.S. attack would be more concentrated and more
serious than a number of bombing and cruise missile attacks on
Iraq launched since the end of the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
"If it should come to military action, the kind of campaign
that would be undertaken would be significant. It would be far
more that what has been experienced in the past, certainly since
the Persian Gulf War," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Republican lawmakers on Tuesday rejected Iraq's
invitation to visit Baghdad to check by themselves if there are
any weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's invitation was delivered by its U.N. ambassador on
Monday, which said U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich could lead a
congressional delegation to inspect Iraqi presidential sites for
prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
But Republican lawmakers said it was in vain for Saddam to try
to drive a wedge between them and President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"If he is looking for a rift between the Congress and the
president on that subject, he is not going to find it," House
Majority leader Dick Armey said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority leader Trent Lott called for decisive military
action against Saddam, saying: "If we're going to do this, let's
go all the way."
</P>
<P>
He said it was essential for the United States to have a clear
"endgame" if it proceeded with military action, and it made no
sense to put Saddam "back in his cage and then have him back out
in six months."
</P>
<P>
"Let's hit him hard, right up front," Lott said, urging strikes
to "take out" suspected chemical and biological weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
"Take out the palace guard, take out the palaces, take out
every ... target and hope that you can put one missile down in
an event or a building where Saddam Hussein is," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Republicans Reject Iraq's Invitation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican lawmakers on
Tuesday rejected Iraq's offer to visit Baghdad to check by
themselves if there are any weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's invitation was delivered by its U.N. ambassador on
Monday, which said U.S. House Speaker Newt Gingrich could lead a
congressional delegation to inspect Iraqi presidential sites for
prohibited weapons.
</P>
<P>
But Republican lawmakers said it was in vain for Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein to try to drive a wedge between them
and President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"If he is looking for a rift between the Congress and the
president on that subject, he is not going to find it," House
Majority leader Dick Armey said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority leader Trent Lott called for decisive
military action against Saddam, saying: "If we're going to do
this, let's go all the way."
</P>
<P>
He said, "Let's hit him (Saddam)hard, right up front," Lott
said, urging strikes to "take out" suspected chemical and
biological weapons sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
