<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, U.S. Make No Breakthrough in Helms-Burton Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 3(Xinhua) -- No breakthroughs have been made
in talks in Brussels between the United States and the European
Union (EU) on a dispute over U.S. sanction laws, it was learned
here today.
</P>
<P>
European Trade Commissioner Sir Leon Brittan and U.S.
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat held a 90-minute session
of talks in Brussels Tuesday, which dealt mainly with U.S. laws
that threaten to punish foreign companies doing business with
Cuba, Iran and Libya, Brittan's spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, the spokesman said the talks were "constructive and
practical."
</P>
<P>
"There was no breakthrough, but on both extraterritorial
questions and the questions of expropriation, there was a useful
exchange and the discussions will continue," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added Brittan wanted to stress that there had to be progress
in parallel on both the issue of extraterritoriality and on
expropriation "for there to be a deal."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said no deadline was set for completing the
talks. "However, of course, they cannot go on indefinitely," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 Helms-Burton act calls for sanctions against any
foreign company deemed to be using property confiscated during
Cuba's 1959 communist revolution from someone who is now a U.S.
citizen.
</P>
<P>
The Iran-Libya Sanctions Act requires sanctions to be imposed
on foreign firms aiding those countries' energy sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
