<HEADLINE> Turkey Urges Iraq to Be Flexible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz on Tuesday called on Iraq to adopt a flexible policy to
avert a military strike by the United States, according to local
TV reports.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, who was on a visit to the Black Sea city of Rize, told
reporters that Ankara's primary objective is to eliminate the
circumstances that may lead to a conflict in the region.
</P>
<P>
"If Iraq does not take our warning into consideration, it will
lose the chance that Turkey would react to the incoming
developments," Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
On Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem's planned visit to
Baghdad, Yilmaz stressed that Cem would tell the Iraqi leadership
about the determination of the United States to attack Iraq if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
As the Iraqi government denied the United Nations arms
inspection team's access to the presidential palace, Washington
had voiced that it would resort to force to make Iraq give in.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that Yilmaz's remark indicated that
Ankara would extend tacit support toward a possible U.S. strike
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, however, said that the U.S. administration had not
made any request of using the Incirlik air base in southern Turkey
which was used by Western jets during the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Turkey had already taken all measures for its
own security if a military conflict broke out between Iraq and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit had made it clear
that Turkey would not like to see a new war in the region, saying
that Turkey had suffered a lot from the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's official statistics show that Turkey had an economic
loss totaling 35 billion U.S. dollars as a result of the
U.N. embargo on Iraq which was an import trading partner of
Turkey in the past.
</P>
<P>
Cem is due to visit Baghdad Wednesday and start talks with the
Iraqi leadership Thursday on the current tense situation.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to meet with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein,
conveying to him Turkey's attitude on the issue, according to an
official statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
