<HEADLINE> Armenian President Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Armenian President Levon
Ter-Petrosyan Tuesday evening announced his resignation at the
national television, the Itar-Tass news agency reported from
Yerevan, capital of Armenia.
</P>
<P>
The president's resignation was forced by a political crisis
brought about by a clash of approaches in the Armenian leadership
to the solution of the Nagorno-Karabakh issue.
</P>
<P>
The Erkrapa group, the majority party in the Armenian
parliament, on Tuesday made a public statement in parliament,
accusing the president and the ruling party "The Armenian National
Movement", of pursuing "a defeatist policy that poses a threat to
security of both Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh."
</P>
<P>
Erkrapa leader Albert Bazeyan, who read out the statement in
parliament, declared that contradictions over the settlement in
Nagorno-Karabakh had evolved into a political crisis. In
conditions of the crisis, a realignment of party factions and
deputy groups was taking place in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Norik Petrosyan representing the communist faction announced in
parliament that participants in the numerous meetings called by
the communist party in the cities and districts of Armenia over
the past few days called for the resignation of the president and
the entire government of Armenia, their final withdrawal from the
political arena and the formation of a national salvation
government.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the current political crisis in
Armenia emerged after the presidential Security Council examined
the proposals made recently by the co-chairmen of the OSCE Minsk
conference on Nagorno-Karabkh or the settlement of the crisis over
the Armenian enclave in neighboring Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
The president and the ruling party found acceptable the
proposals tabled by Russia, the United States and France as the
co-chairs of the OSCE Minsk conference, but Prime Minister Robert
Kocharyan, who had been president of the self-proclaimed republic
of Nagorno-Karabakh until last Spring, categorically rejected the
possibility of returning to Azerbaijan the areas which were
occupied by the Karabakh troops during the 4-year-old armed
conflict with Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the president found himself robbed of support of
the "power" ministries whose leaders openly rejected compliance
with the president's policy with regard to Nagorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Tuesday, the president accepted the resignation of
mayor of Yerevan Vano Siradegyan, the head of the ruling party
"The Armenian national movement". A day before, Minister of
Foreign Affairs of Armenia Alexander Arzumanyan had stepped down.
</P>
<P>
Levon Ter-Petrosyan was elected president of Armenia on October
16, 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
