<HEADLINE> Powerful Storms Hit U.S. Southeast, West Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands of
customers were blacked out in southeast and west coast of the
United States Monday and Tuesday following powerful storms that were
accompanied with tornadoes across southern Florida and California.
</P>
<P>
A storm blew in from the Gulf of Mexico and moved slowly
northward, striking states along the East Coast. At least four
tornadoes hit the Miami area and another struck near Fort
Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
The storm left as many as 220,000 customers without power Tuesday
and drove ships aground. At least one person was killed.
</P>
<P>
A gust to 85 mph (136 kph) hit the Florida Keys Monday night.
Several people were injured by flying debris in Key West and a
police helicopter and two small airplanes sitting at the city's
airport were overturned by wind.
</P>
<P>
At Miami International Airport, gust to 104 mph (165 kph) was
reported Monday night, forcing a brief closure of the airport.
</P>
<P>
A second major storm struck California, blacking out more than
100,00 customers Tuesday and causing flooding that shut down Amtrak
train service along the whole West Coast and closed highways. Part
of the Napa Valley wine country was inundated and Los Angeles
streets were flooded.
</P>
<P>
Flood warnings were posted Tuesday for parts of California in the
West and North Carolina and Tennessee in the East, with coastal
flood watches on the Atlantic shore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
