<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright: US Prefers Diplomatic Solution to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright said here Tuesday that Washington still prefers a
diplomatic solution to the crisis of arms inspection in Iraq by
the United Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
"We would prefer a diplomatic solution, but if we do take
military actions, it will be significant," Albright said at a
joint press conference with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who arrived here Tuesday after visiting Bahrain, held
talks respectively with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Moussa Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to thwart Saddam Hussein's ability to acquire and
develop weapons of mass destruction or to threaten its neighbors,"
Albright said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred the arms inspectors of the UNSCOM in charge of
eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction from searching
presidential palaces suspected of hiding banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to take military actions to
force Iraq to grant free access to the arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
While pressing a demand for unrestricted inspections in Iraq,
Albright gave a certain room for diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that diplomacy will convince Saddam to turn away from
his collision course with the world but we are in absolute accord
that the only standard for a real diplomatic solution is full
compliance with the Security Council and unconditional, unfettered
access for U.N. weapons inspectors," she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
She also said that the U.S. has no quarrels with the Iraqi
people and is pushing for the expansion of the oil-for-food
program.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan asked the Security Council to
double the amount of oil that Iraq can sell under the oil-for-food
deal which allows Iraq to export 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of
oil over six months to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Albright said she has "excellent discussions" with Mubarak on
all the options, which have capped meetings she has held with
U.S. allies in Europe and the Mideast region since last Wednesday
to rally support for a possible military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Today I can report to you, the U.S., Egypt, Jordan, Kuwait,
Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, and the Palestinian (National) Authority
are one mind," she said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Moussa stressed that Egypt is doing its best
to channel the current tensions in the Gulf to a diplomatic
solution.
</P>
<P>
"It is very important that there will be full compliance with
Security Council resolutions, and to guarantee full cooperation
between the UNSCOM and Iraq. At the same time, diplomatic efforts
should continue ... to avoid grave consequences," he said.
</P>
<P>
Crowning the flurry of contacts among Arab leaders, Arab
League Secretary General Esmat Abdel Meguid will visit Baghdad on
Wednesday to convey a message to President Saddam from the leaders
of Arab League member states.
</P>
<P>
"He will talk with President Saddam that compliance with the
U.N. Security Council and work to avoid the grave consequences of
military options are very important. And what we need is to give
diplomatic efforts the chance to bring us back on track," said
Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Touching upon the Mideast peace process, Albright voiced
her disappointment with the 10-month deadlock in the talks between
the Palestinians and Israelis, saying it is high time for
"decision-making," instead of "hand-ringing."
</P>
<P>
Albright is on her way back to Washington at the end of a tour
which has taken her to Britain, Spain, France, Israel, the
Palestinian self-rule areas, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has opposed the use of force against Iraq and exhorted
more diplomatic efforts to defuse the tension in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak held a flurry of telephone consultations with 14 Arab
leaders Monday to ensure there is a common positive Arab stand on
giving diplomacy a full chance to work on the breathtaking
developments in the Iraq-UNSCOM standoff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
