<HEADLINE> Independent Prosecutor Presses on with White </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Monica Lewinsky, the former
White House intern who reportedly claims on tape that she had a
sexual affair with U.S. President Bill Clinton and that he urged
her to lie about it under oath, left Washington on Tuesday for
California, where her father lives.
</P>
<P>
Independent counsel Kenneth Starr's grand jury investigating
the allegations against Clinton, heard testimony on Tuesday from
another former intern, Caroline Self.
</P>
<P>
Former top White House aide George Stephanopoulos also arrived
at the federal courthouse to testify before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
Self, who worked in the office of Clinton's personal secretary
Betty Currie, was believed to have signed for packages Lewinsky
sent to the White House by courier, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Self emerged from the grand jury session to say she did not
know Lewinsky and was unaware of any affair.
</P>
<P>
"I know of no improper relationship between the president and
Monica Lewinsky or any other White House intern," reports quoted
Self as saying.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has strongly denied having an affair or urging Lewinsky
to lie.
</P>
<P>
Starr, speaking to CNN outside his office on Tuesday, said, "We
are trying to get to the truth of what would be if proven, serious
charges."
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for Starr's office declined to comment on a CBS
report on Monday that Starr was leaning toward sending any
evidence against Clinton to the U.S. House of Representatives for
use in possible impeachment proceedings, rather than seeking an
indictment himself.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported on Tuesday that Lewinsky was
cleared to enter the White House three dozen times between the
time she left her staff job there in April 1996 to work at the
Pentagon and December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon officials told the Times the trips were unrelated to
her job at the press office there.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he could confirm the record of Lewinsky's visits,
spokesman Joe Lockhart said, "We have provided the information to
the independent counsel. If the independent counsel chooses to
leak the information even though that is a violation of the law,
then it's a decision he needs to make."
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, Clinton's attorney Robert Bennett on
Monday asked a federal judge in Little Rock, Arkansas, to advance
the start of the Jones sexual harassment lawsuit against Clinton
to March 23 from the currently scheduled May 26.
</P>
<P>
In his motion filed with U.S. District Judge Susan Webber
Wright, Bennett said that leaks of pre-trial testimony have
continued in violation of the court's order.  
</P>
</TEXT>
