<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-03 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Materials Found to Improve Cancer Therapy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli scientists at the
Weizmann Institute have developed new materials that can
significantly improve the promising cancer therapy, the
Photodynamic therapy (PDT), the institute announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the institute's spokesman's office
said the new materials were derived from chlorophyll, the green
pigment that allows plants to capture sunlight. These materials
can overcome the problems that the PDT therapy is facing in
treating bulky and solid tumors.
</P>
<P>
The Photodynamic therapy, which uses light to activate
cancer-killing drugs to destroy tumors, has generated enormous
interest in the medical world in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The therapy uses drugs that become toxic only when exposed to
light. The drug is injected into the bloodstream or the tumor,
then the tumor is exposed to light in a controlled manner so that
the drug is activated to destroy tumor cells while having little
side effects on healthy tissues.
</P>
<P>
But the PDT therapy has several limitations: it is effective
only against relatively flat and thin tumors, such as certain
types of skin and bladder cancers, and patients undergoing such
therapy must avoid the sun for weeks following the treatment
because their skin becomes overly sensitive to strong light.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, existing light-sensitive materials used clinically as
PDT drugs are most commonly based on heme, the red pigment
derived from hemoglobin. They are activated only by visible
light, which has limited tissue-penetrating capacity. And they
work only in the presence of oxygen, which is in short supply
inside many bulky tumors. Thus, current PDT therapy can destroy
only flat and thin tumors.
</P>
<P>
But the new "green" materials, developed by Professor Avigdor
Scherz of the Plant Sciences Department and Yoram Salomon of the
Biological Regulation Department, may make it possible to apply
PDT to bulky and solid tumors and the patients need to avoid the
sun for only a day or two after treatment.
</P>
<P>
These materials can absorb not only visible light, but also
near-infrared light that penetrates much deeper into body
tissues. And they can also work under hypoxic conditions, where
oxygen levels in tissues are below normal.
</P>
<P>
In order to deliver the "green" materials precisely to the
desired site, the scientists can attach them to antibodies, or
other molecules, that act as "guided missiles," transporting the
materials to the targeted place. When illuminated, the materials
will first destroy the blood vessels that feed the tumor, thus
killing the tumor.
</P>
<P>
Clinical tests on mice have proven to be very successful, and
the scientists will soon begin testing them in humans.
</P>
<P>
"If successful, in the future, our 'green' PDT could be a
powerful new tool in the struggle against cancer," Scherz said.
</P>
<P>
The release said that the Dutch company Steba Beheer NV is now
developing the materials for clinical use worldwide. The company
will soon begin having clinical trials worldwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980204.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-03 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Deputy PM Opposes US Military Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit said Tuesday that any use of force by the United
States in ending the current Iraqi crisis would be proof of the
failure of Washington's policies in this region, the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey,
Ecevit warned that Turkey might face a fait accompli situation
regarding any eventual use of the Incirlik air base in Adana,
southern Turkey, by the U.S. forces to strike on Iraq, saying that
Turkish officials should be prudent and cautious on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. fighter jets took off from the Incirlik base and
bombarded northern Iraq during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has so far received no request from the U.S. to
use the air base in southern Turkey to stage strikes against
Iraq to end the current the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Referring to reports that the U.S. did not welcome Turkish
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem's visit to Baghdad, Ecevit
said: "Turkey's initiative is not America's or any other country's
business. Cem's visit (to Baghdad), as you know, was approved by
the U.N. Secretary General (Kofi Annan)...The United States
should take into account Turkey's initiative."
</P>
<P>
Cem will go to Baghdad Wednesday noon to send a message
of Turkish President Suleyman Demirel to Iraqi leaders in a
bid to contribute to a solution to the crisis. 
</P>
